{"title_page": "Ava Helen Pauling", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Ava Helen Pauling\n|image       = Ava Helen Pauling. Pasadena, California. 1948.jpg\n|caption     = Ava Helen Pauling, Pasadena, California (1948)\n|birth_name  = Ava Helen Miller\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1903|12|24}}\n|birth_place = [[Beavercreek, Oregon]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1981|12|7|1903|12|24}}\n|known_for   = [[Humanitarianism|Humanitarian]] achievements\n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Linus Pauling|Linus Carl Pauling]]|June 17, 1923}}\n|children    = 4\n}}\n\n'''Ava Helen Pauling''' (born '''Miller'''; December 24, 1903 \u2013 December 7, 1981) was an American [[human rights]] activist and wife of [[Nobel Prize]] winner [[Linus Pauling]].  Throughout her life, she was involved in various social movements including [[women's rights]], [[Desegregation|racial equality]], and [[World peace|international peace]].\n\nAn avid [[New Deal]]er, Ava Helen Pauling was heavily interested in American politics and social reforms. She is credited with introducing Linus Pauling to the field of [[Peace and conflict studies|peace studies]], for which he received the 1962 [[Nobel Peace Prize]]. Most prominent among the various causes she supported was the issue of ending [[nuclear proliferation]].  Ava Helen Pauling worked with her husband, advocating a stop to the production and use of [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear arms]]. Their campaigning helped lead to the [[Limited Test Ban Treaty]] between the United States and the [[Soviet Union]], effectively ending the above-ground testing of nuclear weapons.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nAva Helen Miller, the tenth of twelve children, was raised on a {{convert|160|acre|km2|adj=on}} farm outside [[Beavercreek, Oregon]].<ref name=\"Hager 1995 69\">{{cite book|last=Hager|first=Thomas|title=Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=1995|page=[https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/69 69]|isbn=0-684-80909-5|url=https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/69}}</ref>  Her father, George Miller, a school teacher, and her mother, Elnora Gard Miller,<ref name=\"Chris Petersen 2006 193\">{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 3|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=193|isbn=0-9629082-6-6}}</ref> expressed [[Socialism|socialist]] ideals and encouraged liberal thinking and discussion in the home.<ref name=\"Hager 1995 69\" /> Linus Pauling explained, \"Ava Helen had been interested in social, political and economic problems ever since she was a teenager. She used to argue with a friend of the family, one of the judges of the [[Oregon Supreme Court|Oregon State Supreme Court]]. She had a general interest in science and was very able, very smart, but she was really concerned about human beings. The humanistic concern she had was very great.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/quotes/ava_helen_pauling.html|title=Quotes by or Related to Ava Helen Pauling (Quote 4 of 8)|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-18 }}</ref>\"\n\nAt the age of thirteen, two years after the divorce of her parents, Ava Helen moved to [[Salem, Oregon]], to live with her sister. She graduated from Salem High School in May 1918, three years after entering,<ref name=\"Chris Petersen 2006 193\"/> and then enrolled in the Oregon Agricultural College, now [[Oregon State University]].\n\n===Higher education===\n[[File:Ava Helen Miller and Linus Pauling, 1922.jpg|thumb|Ava Helen Miller and Linus Pauling, Oregon Agricultural College Graduation Day, Corvallis, OR (1922)]]\nIt was at OAC in 1922 that Ava Helen Miller first met Linus Pauling.  As an [[undergraduate]], he taught a [[chemistry]] course to [[home economics]] majors.  Ava Helen Pauling was enrolled in this course and it was through the student-teacher relationship that they became romantically involved.  After a brief courtship, the two were married on June 17, 1923.<ref>{{cite book|last=Paradowski|first=Robert J.|title=Linus Pauling: A Man of Intellect and Action|publisher=Cosmos Japan International|year=1991|pages=191|isbn=4-938264-01-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Thomas Hager|author2=Cliff Mead|title=Linus Pauling: Scientist and Peacemaker|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2001|pages=5\u20136|isbn=0-87071-489-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 3|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=188|isbn=0-9629082-6-6}}</ref>\n\n===Marriage===\nIn the early years of her marriage, Ava Helen Pauling worked as a part-time laboratory assistant at the [[California Institute of Technology]] for her husband by taking notes, making models and completing other small tasks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/rnb/02/02-081-large.html|title=Research Notebook 002, Page 81|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hager|first=Thomas|title=Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=1995|page=[https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/173 173]|isbn=0-684-80909-5|url=https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/173}}</ref>  Eventually, the couple had four children: Linus Carl Jr. (b. 1925); Peter Jeffress (1931\u20132003); Edward Crellin (1937\u20131997); and Linda Helen, (b. 1932). As the family grew, Ava Helen Pauling worked to create a home environment that would allow her husband to continue his scientific work without domestic distractions.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hager|first=Thomas|title=Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=1995|page=[https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/174 174]|isbn=0-684-80909-5|url=https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/174}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Daisaku Ikeda|author2=Linus Pauling|title=A Lifelong Quest for Peace: A Dialogue|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780867202786|url-access=registration|publisher = Jones and Bartlett|year=1992|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780867202786/page/10 10]|ISBN = 0-86720-278-5}}</ref> Both Ava and her husband were atheists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paulingblog.wordpress.com/2010/07/29/the-paulings-and-unitarianism/|title=The Paulings and Unitarianism|date=July 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n\n===Japanese internment===\nAfter the [[Japan]]ese attack on [[Pearl Harbor]] on December 7, 1941, the United States government proposed the [[internment]] of all [[West Coast of the United States|west coast]] Japanese and [[Japanese American]]s in inland camps out of fear of [[espionage]]. Ava Helen Pauling vigorously opposed this decision by joining the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] and working to raise awareness about the government action. When asked by the ACLU, she and her husband provided employment for a Japanese-American man recently released from an American internment camp. Subsequently, the Pauling family was plied with criticism for what were seen as pro-Japanese actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/corr/bio2.001.1-19450307b.html|title=Anonymous Anti-Japanese Note to Linus Pauling. March 7, 1945.|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/newsclips/bio2.001.1-19450307a.html |title=\"Jap Flag Painted on Garage Door.\" March 7, 1945.|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/corr/bio2.001.2-anonymous-lp-19450309.html|title=Transcript of an Anonymous Letter Sent to Linus Pauling. March 9, 1945.|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref>  The Paulings, however, continued to support the rights of Japanese-Americans throughout [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page3.html|title=Anti-Japanese Sentiment|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Union Now===\nThe [[Federal Union|Union Now]] movement arose from the publication of [[Clarence Streit]]'s novel ''Union Now'', which encouraged nations to combine into a [[democracy|democratic]] [[federation]]. Ava Helen Pauling advocated this movement and encouraged her husband to become educated on Streit's philosophy.  As a result, Linus Pauling became publicly involved in the cause, eventually joining the [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] chapter of Federal Union, the organizational outgrowth of Union Now. In 1940, thanks in part to Ava Helen's suggestion, Linus Pauling gave his first political speech, urging his audience to consider Union Now as a movement toward a viable system of government. This effectively began Pauling's career as a public proponent of peace and human rights.<ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 3|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=206\u2013208|isbn=0-9629082-6-6}}</ref>\n\n===Women's rights===\nAva Helen was deeply involved in the movement for women's rights. Following World War II, she became a member of the [[Women's International League for Peace and Freedom]], or WILPF, [[Women Strike for Peace]] and Women Act for Disarmament, an international federation of women's groups in which she held the position of honorary chairwoman.<ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 3|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=201\u2013202|isbn=0-9629082-6-6}}</ref>  She also worked to bring together fellow [[peace activist|activists]] in support of women, helping to organize the \"Women's Peace March\" in Europe.<ref name=\"Anitra Carr, Ph.D\">{{cite web|url=http://lpi.oregonstate.edu/ss01/avpauling.html|title=Ava Helen Pauling|publisher=The Linus Pauling Institute|accessdate=2007-12-19|author=Anitra Carr, Ph.D.| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071225090947/http://lpi.oregonstate.edu/ss01/avpauling.html| archivedate= 25 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  In addition to her membership in various women's organizations, Ava Helen served as three time national vice-president for WILPF, one of the many women-led groups that supported the Paulings' peace efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page21.html|title=Linus Pauling and the International Peace Movement Narrative: Peace Groups|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hager|first=Thomas|title=Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=1995|pages=[https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/505 505, 515, 537]|isbn=0-684-80909-5|url=https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/505}}</ref>\n\n===Nuclear disarmament and world peace===\nFor much of her life, Ava Helen Pauling made world peace her primary political concern. During the [[Cold War]], she and her husband protested against nuclear armament and worked to increase public awareness of the danger of [[Nuclear warfare|nuclear war]]. Even after Linus Pauling came under fire from the [[United States Senate Subcommittee on Internal Security|Senate Internal Security Subcommittee]], or SISS, the Paulings continued to campaign for global peace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/newsclips/bio2.021.12.html|title=Reluctant Pauling Gets Ultimatum on Petition|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref>  Ava Helen Pauling traveled throughout the United States and [[Europe]] giving speeches emphasizing the importance of peace. She was also instrumental in bringing together various groups in marches and rallies to protest U.S. military policy and [[McCarthyism]]. After collecting over 9,000 signatures from scientists worldwide, in 1958 the Paulings presented the [[United Nations]] with a petition demanding an end to atmospheric nuclear weapons testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page27.html|title=Linus Pauling and the International Peace Movement: The Right to Petition|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-20}}</ref>  In 1963, President [[John F. Kennedy]] and [[Nikita Khrushchev]] signed the Partial Test Ban Treaty. The signing of this treaty directly resulted in Linus Pauling's receipt of the 1962 Nobel Peace Prize, his second unshared Nobel Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page45.html|title=The Peace Prize...|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071217184243/http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page45.html| archivedate= 17 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> In an interview which aired on the [[Nova (American TV program)|Nova TV series]] in 1977, Ava Helen Pauling explained:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/video/1977v.1-avahelen.html|title=Linus Pauling, Crusading Scientist: Encouragement from Ava Helen|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 5|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=8|isbn=0-9629082-8-2}}</ref>\n{{quote|I, in talking with [Linus] thought that it was of course important that he do his work, but if the world were destroyed, then the work would not be of any value. So that he should take part of his time and devote it to [[peaceworker|peace work]] as we called it. I felt a little guilty about this because of course I knew very well what great and deep pleasure he got from his scientific work, how competent he was in his scientific work, and how enthusiastic he was about it.}}\n\n==Legacy==\nAva Helen Pauling died on December 7, 1981 after a long battle with [[stomach cancer]] and subsequent [[Internal bleeding|internal hemorrhaging]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/newsclips/ahp3.004.16.html|title=Ava Pauling, 77, Wife of Scientist|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of her efforts for peace and equality, Oregon State University's College of [[Liberal arts|Liberal Arts]] established the Ava Helen Pauling Lectureship on World Peace, now known as the Pauling Peace Lectureship, in 1982. The inaugural lecturer was Linus Pauling and subsequent lecturers have included [[Paul Warnke]], [[Helen Caldicott]], [[Noam Chomsky]], and [[Arun Manilal Gandhi|Arun Gandhi]].  Additionally, the [[Linus Pauling Institute]] chose to honor her with an [[Financial endowment|endowed position]], the Ava Helen Pauling Chair, in 1996.<ref name=\"Anitra Carr, Ph.D\" /><ref>{{cite news|first=David |last=Stauth |title=Genetic, Biomedical Researchers Join OSU |url=http://oregonstate.edu/dept/ncs/otw/backissues/2000-2001/jan18.pdf |work=OSU This Week Vol. 40 No. 15. |publisher=Oregon State University |date=2001-01-18 |accessdate=2007-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904100454/http://oregonstate.edu/dept/ncs/otw/backissues/2000-2001/jan18.pdf |archivedate=September 4, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n===Honors and awards===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Doctor of World Law, San Gabriel College, June 19, 1962.\n* Honorary Member: Federated Auxiliaries of the International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's union, June 21, 1967.\n* Mother of the Year Award: California State Association of Colored Women's Clubs, [[Emma Lazarus]], and Jewish Women's Clubs of Los Angeles, 1967.\n* Certificate of Appreciation: [[Anza-Borrego Desert State Park|Anza-Borrego]] Committee of the Desert Protective Council, December 20, 1974.\n* Ralph Atkinson Award of the [[Monterey County, California|Monterey County]] Chapter of the ACLU.\n* Spectrum Award and Medal: World Organization for Human Potential, May 4, 1984.\n* Janice Holland Award of the [[Pennsylvania]] Chapter of the [[Women Strike for Peace]].\n{{refend}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of peace activists]]\n* [[Japanese American Internment]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Thomas Hager|Hager, Thomas]], ''Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling'', [[Simon & Schuster]] (1995) {{ISBN|0-684-80909-5}}.\n* Ikeda, Daisaku & Linus Pauling, ''A Lifelong Quest for Peace: A Dialogue'', (1992) {{ISBN|0-86720-278-5}}.\n* Marinacci, Barbara & Ramesh Krishnamurthy, ''Linus Pauling on Peace: A Scientist Speaks Out on Humanism and World Survival'', Rising Star Press (1998) {{ISBN|0-933670-03-6}}\n* Mead, Clifford & [[Thomas Hager]], ''Linus Pauling: Scientist and Peacemaker'', Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections (2001) {{ISBN|0-87071-489-9}}.\n* Paradowski, Robert J., Emile Zuckerkandl, Joseph Rotblat, Itaru Tanaka, Fumikazu Miyazaki, Z. S. Herman, & D. B. Munro, ''Linus Pauling: A Man of Intellect and Action'', Cosmos Japan International (1991) {{ISBN|4-938264-01-3}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100601161603/http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/index.html The Ava Helen and Linus Pauling Papers]\n* [http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/people/pauling-avahelen.html Digitized Collection of Documents Related to Ava Helen Pauling's Peace Work]\n* [http://www.paulingcatalogue.org/ The Pauling Catalogue]\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n92-110130}}\n\n{{Linus Pauling|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pauling, Ava Helen}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:Oregon State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Corvallis, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Deaths from stomach cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:People from Salem, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Women's International League for Peace and Freedom people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Ava Helen Pauling\n|image       = Ava Helen Pauling. Pasadena, California. 1948.jpg\n|caption     = Ava Helen Pauling, Pasadena, California (1948)\n|birth_name  = Ava Helen Miller\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1903|12|24}}\n|birth_place = [[Beavercreek, Oregon]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1981|12|7|1903|12|24}}\n|known_for   = [[Humanitarianism|Humanitarian]] achievements\n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Linus Pauling|Linus Carl Pauling]]|June 17, 1923}}\n|children    = 4\n}}\n\n'''Ava Helen Pauling''' (born '''Miller'''; December 24, 1903 \u2013 December 7, 1981) was an American [[human rights]] activist and wife of [[Nobel Prize]] winner [[Linus Pauling]].  Throughout her life, she was involved in various social movements including [[women's rights]], [[Desegregation|racial equality]], and [[World peace|international peace]].\n\nAn avid [[New Deal]]er, Ava Helen Pauling was heavily interested in American politics and social reforms. She is credited with introducing Linus Pauling to the field of [[Peace and conflict studies|peace studies]], for which he received the 1962 [[Nobel Peace Prize]]. Most prominent among the various causes she supported was the issue of ending [[nuclear proliferation]].  Ava Helen Pauling worked with her husband, advocating a stop to the production and use of [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear arms]]. Their campaigning helped lead to the [[Limited Test Ban Treaty]] between the United States and the [[Soviet Union]], effectively ending the above-ground testing of nuclear weapons.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nAva Helen Miller, the tenth of twelve children, was raised on a {{convert|160|acre|km2|adj=on}} farm outside [[Beavercreek, Oregon]].<ref name=\"Hager 1995 69\">{{cite book|last=Hager|first=Thomas|title=Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=1995|page=[https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/69 69]|isbn=0-684-80909-5|url=https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/69}}</ref>  Her father, George Miller, a school teacher, and her mother, Elnora Gard Miller,<ref name=\"Chris Petersen 2006 193\">{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 3|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=193|isbn=0-9629082-6-6}}</ref> expressed [[Socialism|socialist]] ideals and encouraged liberal thinking and discussion in the home.<ref name=\"Hager 1995 69\" /> Linus Pauling explained, \"Ava Helen had been interested in social, political and economic problems ever since she was a teenager. She used to argue with a friend of the family, one of the judges of the [[Oregon Supreme Court|Oregon State Supreme Court]]. She had a general interest in science and was very able, very smart, but she was really concerned about human beings. The humanistic concern she had was very great.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/quotes/ava_helen_pauling.html|title=Quotes by or Related to Ava Helen Pauling (Quote 4 of 8)|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-18 }}</ref>\"\n\nAt the age of thirteen, two years after the divorce of her parents, Ava Helen moved to [[Salem, Oregon]], to live with her sister. She graduated from Salem High School in May 1918, three years after entering,<ref name=\"Chris Petersen 2006 193\"/> and then enrolled in the Oregon Agricultural College, now [[Oregon State University]].\n\n===Higher education===\n[[File:Ava Helen Miller and Linus Pauling, 1922.jpg|thumb|Ava Helen Miller and Linus Pauling, Oregon Agricultural College Graduation Day, Corvallis, OR (1922)]]\nIt was at OAC in 1922 that Ava Helen Miller first met Linus Pauling.  As an [[undergraduate]], he taught a [[chemistry]] course to [[home economics]] majors.  Ava Helen Pauling was enrolled in this course and it was through the student-teacher relationship that they became romantically involved.  After a brief courtship, the two were married on June 17, 1923.<ref>{{cite book|last=Paradowski|first=Robert J.|title=Linus Pauling: A Man of Intellect and Action|publisher=Cosmos Japan International|year=1991|pages=191|isbn=4-938264-01-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Thomas Hager|author2=Cliff Mead|title=Linus Pauling: Scientist and Peacemaker|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2001|pages=5\u20136|isbn=0-87071-489-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 3|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=188|isbn=0-9629082-6-6}}</ref>\n\n===Marriage===\nIn the early years of her marriage, Ava Helen Pauling worked as a part-time laboratory assistant at the [[California Institute of Technology]] for her husband by taking notes, making models and completing other small tasks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/rnb/02/02-081-large.html|title=Research Notebook 002, Page 81|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hager|first=Thomas|title=Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=1995|page=[https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/173 173]|isbn=0-684-80909-5|url=https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/173}}</ref>  Eventually, the couple had four children: Linus Carl Jr. (b. 1925); Peter Jeffress (1931\u20132003); Edward Crellin (1937\u20131997); and Linda Helen, (b. 1932). As the family grew, Ava Helen Pauling worked to create a home environment that would allow her husband to continue his scientific work without domestic distractions.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hager|first=Thomas|title=Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=1995|page=[https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/174 174]|isbn=0-684-80909-5|url=https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/174}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Daisaku Ikeda|author2=Linus Pauling|title=A Lifelong Quest for Peace: A Dialogue|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780867202786|url-access=registration|publisher = Jones and Bartlett|year=1992|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780867202786/page/10 10]|ISBN = 0-86720-278-5}}</ref> Both Ava and her husband were atheists.<ref>[https://paulingblog.wordpress.com/2010/07/29/the-paulings-and-unitarianism/ (n.d.): n. pag. Web. \"both Linus and Ava Helen Pauling were avowed atheists\"]</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n\n===Japanese internment===\nAfter the [[Japan]]ese attack on [[Pearl Harbor]] on December 7, 1941, the United States government proposed the [[internment]] of all [[West Coast of the United States|west coast]] Japanese and [[Japanese American]]s in inland camps out of fear of [[espionage]]. Ava Helen Pauling vigorously opposed this decision by joining the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] and working to raise awareness about the government action. When asked by the ACLU, she and her husband provided employment for a Japanese-American man recently released from an American internment camp. Subsequently, the Pauling family was plied with criticism for what were seen as pro-Japanese actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/corr/bio2.001.1-19450307b.html|title=Anonymous Anti-Japanese Note to Linus Pauling. March 7, 1945.|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/newsclips/bio2.001.1-19450307a.html |title=\"Jap Flag Painted on Garage Door.\" March 7, 1945.|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/corr/bio2.001.2-anonymous-lp-19450309.html|title=Transcript of an Anonymous Letter Sent to Linus Pauling. March 9, 1945.|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref>  The Paulings, however, continued to support the rights of Japanese-Americans throughout [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page3.html|title=Anti-Japanese Sentiment|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Union Now===\nThe [[Federal Union|Union Now]] movement arose from the publication of [[Clarence Streit]]'s novel ''Union Now'', which encouraged nations to combine into a [[democracy|democratic]] [[federation]]. Ava Helen Pauling advocated this movement and encouraged her husband to become educated on Streit's philosophy.  As a result, Linus Pauling became publicly involved in the cause, eventually joining the [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] chapter of Federal Union, the organizational outgrowth of Union Now. In 1940, thanks in part to Ava Helen's suggestion, Linus Pauling gave his first political speech, urging his audience to consider Union Now as a movement toward a viable system of government. This effectively began Pauling's career as a public proponent of peace and human rights.<ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 3|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=206\u2013208|isbn=0-9629082-6-6}}</ref>\n\n===Women's rights===\nAva Helen was deeply involved in the movement for women's rights. Following World War II, she became a member of the [[Women's International League for Peace and Freedom]], or WILPF, [[Women Strike for Peace]] and Women Act for Disarmament, an international federation of women's groups in which she held the position of honorary chairwoman.<ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 3|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=201\u2013202|isbn=0-9629082-6-6}}</ref>  She also worked to bring together fellow [[peace activist|activists]] in support of women, helping to organize the \"Women's Peace March\" in Europe.<ref name=\"Anitra Carr, Ph.D\">{{cite web|url=http://lpi.oregonstate.edu/ss01/avpauling.html|title=Ava Helen Pauling|publisher=The Linus Pauling Institute|accessdate=2007-12-19|author=Anitra Carr, Ph.D.| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071225090947/http://lpi.oregonstate.edu/ss01/avpauling.html| archivedate= 25 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>  In addition to her membership in various women's organizations, Ava Helen served as three time national vice-president for WILPF, one of the many women-led groups that supported the Paulings' peace efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page21.html|title=Linus Pauling and the International Peace Movement Narrative: Peace Groups|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hager|first=Thomas|title=Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=1995|pages=[https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/505 505, 515, 537]|isbn=0-684-80909-5|url=https://archive.org/details/forceofnaturelif00hage/page/505}}</ref>\n\n===Nuclear disarmament and world peace===\nFor much of her life, Ava Helen Pauling made world peace her primary political concern. During the [[Cold War]], she and her husband protested against nuclear armament and worked to increase public awareness of the danger of [[Nuclear warfare|nuclear war]]. Even after Linus Pauling came under fire from the [[United States Senate Subcommittee on Internal Security|Senate Internal Security Subcommittee]], or SISS, the Paulings continued to campaign for global peace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/newsclips/bio2.021.12.html|title=Reluctant Pauling Gets Ultimatum on Petition|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref>  Ava Helen Pauling traveled throughout the United States and [[Europe]] giving speeches emphasizing the importance of peace. She was also instrumental in bringing together various groups in marches and rallies to protest U.S. military policy and [[McCarthyism]]. After collecting over 9,000 signatures from scientists worldwide, in 1958 the Paulings presented the [[United Nations]] with a petition demanding an end to atmospheric nuclear weapons testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page27.html|title=Linus Pauling and the International Peace Movement: The Right to Petition|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-20}}</ref>  In 1963, President [[John F. Kennedy]] and [[Nikita Khrushchev]] signed the Partial Test Ban Treaty. The signing of this treaty directly resulted in Linus Pauling's receipt of the 1962 Nobel Peace Prize, his second unshared Nobel Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page45.html|title=The Peace Prize...|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071217184243/http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/narrative/page45.html| archivedate= 17 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> In an interview which aired on the [[Nova (American TV program)|Nova TV series]] in 1977, Ava Helen Pauling explained:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/video/1977v.1-avahelen.html|title=Linus Pauling, Crusading Scientist: Encouragement from Ava Helen|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Petersen|author2=Cliff Mead|title=The Pauling Catalogue, Vol. 5|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|year=2006|pages=8|isbn=0-9629082-8-2}}</ref>\n{{quote|I, in talking with [Linus] thought that it was of course important that he do his work, but if the world were destroyed, then the work would not be of any value. So that he should take part of his time and devote it to [[peaceworker|peace work]] as we called it. I felt a little guilty about this because of course I knew very well what great and deep pleasure he got from his scientific work, how competent he was in his scientific work, and how enthusiastic he was about it.}}\n\n==Legacy==\nAva Helen Pauling died on December 7, 1981 after a long battle with [[stomach cancer]] and subsequent [[Internal bleeding|internal hemorrhaging]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/newsclips/ahp3.004.16.html|title=Ava Pauling, 77, Wife of Scientist|publisher=Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of her efforts for peace and equality, Oregon State University's College of [[Liberal arts|Liberal Arts]] established the Ava Helen Pauling Lectureship on World Peace, now known as the Pauling Peace Lectureship, in 1982. The inaugural lecturer was Linus Pauling and subsequent lecturers have included [[Paul Warnke]], [[Helen Caldicott]], [[Noam Chomsky]], and [[Arun Manilal Gandhi|Arun Gandhi]].  Additionally, the [[Linus Pauling Institute]] chose to honor her with an [[Financial endowment|endowed position]], the Ava Helen Pauling Chair, in 1996.<ref name=\"Anitra Carr, Ph.D\" /><ref>{{cite news|first=David |last=Stauth |title=Genetic, Biomedical Researchers Join OSU |url=http://oregonstate.edu/dept/ncs/otw/backissues/2000-2001/jan18.pdf |work=OSU This Week Vol. 40 No. 15. |publisher=Oregon State University |date=2001-01-18 |accessdate=2007-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904100454/http://oregonstate.edu/dept/ncs/otw/backissues/2000-2001/jan18.pdf |archivedate=September 4, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n===Honors and awards===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Doctor of World Law, San Gabriel College, June 19, 1962.\n* Honorary Member: Federated Auxiliaries of the International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's union, June 21, 1967.\n* Mother of the Year Award: California State Association of Colored Women's Clubs, [[Emma Lazarus]], and Jewish Women's Clubs of Los Angeles, 1967.\n* Certificate of Appreciation: [[Anza-Borrego Desert State Park|Anza-Borrego]] Committee of the Desert Protective Council, December 20, 1974.\n* Ralph Atkinson Award of the [[Monterey County, California|Monterey County]] Chapter of the ACLU.\n* Spectrum Award and Medal: World Organization for Human Potential, May 4, 1984.\n* Janice Holland Award of the [[Pennsylvania]] Chapter of the [[Women Strike for Peace]].\n{{refend}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of peace activists]]\n* [[Japanese American Internment]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Thomas Hager|Hager, Thomas]], ''Force of Nature: The Life of Linus Pauling'', [[Simon & Schuster]] (1995) {{ISBN|0-684-80909-5}}.\n* Ikeda, Daisaku & Linus Pauling, ''A Lifelong Quest for Peace: A Dialogue'', (1992) {{ISBN|0-86720-278-5}}.\n* Marinacci, Barbara & Ramesh Krishnamurthy, ''Linus Pauling on Peace: A Scientist Speaks Out on Humanism and World Survival'', Rising Star Press (1998) {{ISBN|0-933670-03-6}}\n* Mead, Clifford & [[Thomas Hager]], ''Linus Pauling: Scientist and Peacemaker'', Oregon State University Libraries Special Collections (2001) {{ISBN|0-87071-489-9}}.\n* Paradowski, Robert J., Emile Zuckerkandl, Joseph Rotblat, Itaru Tanaka, Fumikazu Miyazaki, Z. S. Herman, & D. B. Munro, ''Linus Pauling: A Man of Intellect and Action'', Cosmos Japan International (1991) {{ISBN|4-938264-01-3}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100601161603/http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/index.html The Ava Helen and Linus Pauling Papers]\n* [http://osulibrary.oregonstate.edu/specialcollections/coll/pauling/peace/people/pauling-avahelen.html Digitized Collection of Documents Related to Ava Helen Pauling's Peace Work]\n* [http://www.paulingcatalogue.org/ The Pauling Catalogue]\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n92-110130}}\n\n{{Linus Pauling|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pauling, Ava Helen}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:Oregon State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Corvallis, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Deaths from stomach cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:People from Salem, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Women's International League for Peace and Freedom people]]\n", "name_user": "Lotje", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 1 