{"title_page": "The Way I See It", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Way I See It\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Raphael Saadiq]]\n| cover      = Raphael Saadiq - The Way I See It.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2008|09|16}}\n| recorded   = 2008\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{hlist|Blakeslee Recording Company in Los Angeles|Harmonie Park in Detroit|The Music Shed in New Orleans}}\n| genre      = [[Soul music|Soul]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=42|s=07}}\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| producer   = Raphael Saadiq\n| prev_title = [[Ray Ray]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title = [[Stone Rollin']]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Way I See It\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Love That Girl]]\n | single1date = August 5, 2008\n | single2     = [[100 Yard Dash]]\n | single2date = March 30, 2009\n | single3     = Never Give You Up\n | single3date = May 27, 2009\n | single4     = Let's Take a Walk\n | single4date = August 7, 2009\n | single5     = Staying in Love\n | single5date = October 5, 2009\n}}\n}}\n'''''The Way I See It''''' is the third album by American [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer, songwriter, and producer [[Raphael Saadiq]]. It was released on September 16, 2008, by [[Columbia Records]].\n\nAfter independently releasing the 2004 album ''[[Ray Ray]]'', Saadiq continued working on other artists' projects and developed a partnership with audio engineer Charles Brungardt, who shared the singer's fascination with historic recording techniques and equipment. In 2008, he returned from a vacation that inspired him to pursue classic [[soul music]] and recorded ''The Way I See It'' primarily at his [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles|North Hollywood]] studio with the engineer.\n\nSaadiq and Brungardt disregarded their previous experience in recording production while making ''The Way I See It''. Instead, they experimented with older recording techniques in an attempt to recreate the [[Motown]] music aesthetic of the 1960s, producing a traditional soul album that draws on the [[Motown#Motown Sound|Motown Sound]] and [[Philadelphia soul]] styles. Saadiq, whose lyrics mostly deal with romantic subject matter, described it as a series of love songs about music and remaining faithful to it despite trends.\n\n''The Way I See It'' was initially overlooked by consumers, but [[record chart|charted]] steadily on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and eventually sold 282,000 copies in the United States by 2011. It also performed well in European countries such as France, where it charted for 51 weeks. The album received mostly positive reviews from critics and was seen as an exemplary release of the classic soul revival at the time. It garnered Saadiq a newer, more diverse audience as he toured extensively in support of the album, performing concerts in the US, Europe, and Asia.\n\n== Background ==\nAfter releasing his second studio album ''[[Ray Ray]]'' in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson |first=MacKenzie |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/raphael-saadiq-mn0000402249 |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=May 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApgXSkbu?url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/raphael-saadiq-mn0000402249 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saadiq continued working as a producer, composer, and instrumentalist on other recording artists' music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/raphael-saadiq-mn0000402249/credits |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 Credits |publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation |accessdate=May 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Apgauhy2?url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/raphael-saadiq-mn0000402249/credits |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was introduced to audio engineer Charles Brungardt through production and songwriting team [[Jake and the Phatman]], who had worked on ''Ray Ray''. Brungardt interned at Blakeslee Recording Company, Saadiq's [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles|North Hollywood]] recording studio, and eventually became his principal sonic partner on projects. The two shared a fascination with historic recording techniques and equipment. They also studied the 2006 book ''[[Recording The Beatles]]'' together and had an interest in the knowledge of recording gear by engineers and technicians for English [[rock music|rock]] band [[The Beatles]].<ref name=\"Britton\">{{cite journal |last=Britton |first=Jack |date=March 2011 |url=http://www.emusician.com/pop/0808/a-modern-throwback/136231 |title=A Modern Throwback |journal=[[Electronic Musician]] |location=New York |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApgdQ1uP?url=http://www.emusician.com/pop/0808/a-modern-throwback/136231 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Brungardt increased his [[audio engineering|engineering]] output, and in 2007, Saadiq enlisted him to engineer and [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]] English singer [[Joss Stone]]'s studio album ''[[Introducing Joss Stone]]'',<ref name=\"Britton\"/> which Saadiq produced.<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite journal|last=Lewis |first=Pete |url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/409/raphael_saadiq_this_years_vintage/ |title=Raphael Saadiq: This Years Vintage |journal=[[Blues & Soul]] |location=London |issue=1020 |date=May 22, 2009 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Apgl4SvN?url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/409/raphael_saadiq_this_years_vintage/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile vacationing in [[the Bahamas]] and [[Costa Rica]] in 2008, Saadiq observed people there listening to classic [[soul music]] and was inspired to pursue it as a musical direction for his next album. He recounted the experience in an interview for ''[[Blues & Soul]]'', saying that \"I was like 'Wow, maybe I should tap into this vibe, because it\u2019s actually what I LOVE!' ... I realised that, though you can hear it in many of the records I've done throughout my career, I'd never paid 100% attention to going in that direction before. So the difference this time is that I took a more focused route.\"<ref name=\"Lewis\"/> As a part of [[Tony! Toni! Ton\u00e9!]] during the late 1980s and 1990s, Saadiq had incorporated influences from the music of [[Motown]] in his songwriting for the group.<ref name=\"Britton\"/> Before recording ''The Way I See It'', Saadiq signed to [[Columbia Records]]. Label executive [[Rick Rubin]] visited Saadiq's home studio and was impressed by his material there. He said of Rubin's visit and advice to him as a solo artist, \"He told me to never box myself in. I just have to be myself. You've got to follow your own path. I've always gone down the road less traveled, but now I do it even more aggressively.\"<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.raphaelsaadiq.com/bio |title=The Official Raphael Saadiq Site |at=Bio |publisher=[[Sony Music Entertainment]] |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66cISWM7n?url=http://www.raphaelsaadiq.com/bio |archivedate=2012-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Recording and production ==\nAfter returning from his vacation, Saadiq started writing and recording ''The Way I See It'', which took four months. In an interview for ''[[Sound on Sound]]'', he discussed his comfort level when returning to Blakeslee Recording Company: \"The music for this album flowed organically, naturally, and since I have my own studio I was able to perfect it and take my time to make it right. I was able to live with it day after day, and I think that had a lot to do with how the album turned out.\" He wrote the songs extemporaneously, often by playing guitar and improvising riffs. He subsequently sung them while playing each instrument one at a time, including guitar, bass, and basic piano parts that he planned to include on the recordings. He attributed this secluded approach to \"the state of the industry\" and idealized \"bounc[ing] ideas off other people, do some writing with them, take the material to my band and say, 'OK, let's cut it,' with the orchestra already there. That's my dream. I'd crank records out weekly if I had staff writers like they did at [[Stax Records|Stax]] and Motown\".<ref name=\"Buskin\">{{cite journal|last=Buskin |first=Richard |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/jun09/articles/saadiq.htm |title=Raphael Saadiq |journal=[[Sound on Sound]] |location=Cambridge |date=June 2009 |accessdate=March 28, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApgpglKm?url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/jun09/articles/saadiq.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:JackAshfordHWOFMar2013.jpg|thumb|[[Jack Ashford]] (pictured in 2013), of [[Motown]]'s [[Funk Brothers]] band, played percussion for several songs.]]\n\nSaadiq recorded mostly at Blakeslee Recording Company;<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> additional sessions took place at Harmonie Park Studios in [[Detroit]] and The Music Shed Studios in [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"credits\">{{cite AV media notes|title=The Way I See It|others=[[Raphael Saadiq]]|year=2008|type=CD liner|publisher=[[Columbia Records]]|id=88697 08585 2|location=New York City}}</ref> While recording, he immersed himself in a composite character of classic soul singers from videos he watched, including [[Al Green]], [[Gladys Knight & the Pips]], the [[Four Tops]], and [[the Temptations]].<ref name=\"Buskin\"/><ref name=\"Nathan\">{{cite journal|last=Nathan |first=David |authorlink=David Nathan (music writer) |url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/328/raphael_saadiq__everything_old_is_new_again/ |title=Raphael Saadiq: Everything Old is New Again |journal=Blues & Soul |location=London |issue=1014 |date=November 2, 2008 |accessdate=April 3, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApgrutJt?url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/328/raphael_saadiq__everything_old_is_new_again/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He recorded his vocals with only Brungardt present in the studio, a preference he felt prevented him from \"looking for answers from somebody who may not really know\".<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> Saadiq said he tended to \"record complete takes, and if something isn't quite right but it's got a feel that I know I can never ever capture again, I'll leave it, even if it's [[flat (music)|flat]]. I mean, there are flat parts on my record, because it's not about perfection, it's about the soul.\"<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> He recorded background vocals for all songs.<ref name=\"Powers\">{{cite news |last=Powers |first=Ann |authorlink=Ann Powers |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/soundboard/2008/08/a-conversation.html |title=Raphael Saadiq connects with classic '60s soul |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=August 15, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66jNPIMk4?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080823153902/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/soundboard/2008/08/a-conversation.html |archivedate=2012-04-06 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saadiq played most of the instruments,<ref name=\"Kot\">{{cite news|last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot |url=http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/turn_it_up/2009/03/raphael-saadiq-a-class-act-on-a-soul-mission.html |title=Turn It Up: Raphael Saadiq: A class act on a soul mission |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=March 3, 2009 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApgwPCRR?url=http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/turn_it_up/2009/03/raphael-saadiq-a-class-act-on-a-soul-mission.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> including drums, guitar, piano, sitar, and bass guitar,<ref name=\"credits\"/> his instrument of choice throughout his career.<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> He viewed the bass playing of [[James Jamerson]] as an integral part of Motown recordings, citing it as the inspiration for his own bass sound on the album.<ref name=\"Kot\"/><ref name=\"Candace\">{{cite web|author=Candace L. |url=http://www.okayplayer.com/stories/raphael-saadiq_s-new-album-throwback-to-that-60s-soul-200805025650.html |title=Raphael Saadiq\u2019s New Album: Throwback To That 60s Soul |publisher=[[Okayplayer]] |date=May 2, 2008 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApgzRLK6?url=http://www.okayplayer.com/stories/raphael-saadiq_s-new-album-throwback-to-that-60s-soul-200805025650.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSaadiq worked with other musicians, including Joss Stone, percussionist [[Jack Ashford]], [[string section|string]] arranger [[Paul Riser]], multi-instrumentalist Bobby Ozuna, singer CJ Hilton, and recording artist [[Stevie Wonder]].<ref name=\"credits\"/> Ashford and Riser were members of [[The Funk Brothers]], a group of session musicians for Motown Records during the 1960s.<ref name=\"Lewis\"/> Ashford played tambourine, vibraphone, bells, and shakers on songs such as \"[[100 Yard Dash]]\", \"[[Love That Girl]]\", and \"Staying in Love\".<ref name=\"Farinella\">{{cite journal |last=Farinella |first=David John |date=January 1, 2009 |url=http://mixonline.com/recording/tracking/music-raphael-saadiq/ |title=Music: Raphael Saadiq |journal=[[Mix (magazine)|Mix]] |accessdate=April 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aph2MMiv?url=http://mixonline.com/recording/tracking/music-raphael-saadiq/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ozuna, one-half of Jake and the Phatman,<ref name=\"Britton\"/> co-produced and co-wrote three songs and played several instruments, including bongos, tambourine, and drums.<ref name=\"credits\"/> Hilton co-wrote \"Never Give You Up\" and played its drum and keyboard parts.<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> Wonder's contribution of a harmonica solo on the song was impromptu, as Saadiq reached out to Wonder after recording the song's vocal parts with the improvised line, \"I'd like to invite Mr. Stevie Wonder to my album. Come on, Stevie!\"<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> After having the idea recommended to him by rapper [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]], Saadiq also reached out to [[Jay-Z]] to record a featured rap for a [[remix]] of \"Oh Girl\";<ref name=\"Lewis\"/> it was included on the album as a [[bonus track]].<ref name=\"Kellman\">{{cite web|last=Kellman |first=Andy |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-way-i-see-it-mw0000795539 |title=The Way I See It \u2013 Raphael Saadiq |publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation |accessdate=May 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aph5D7j2?url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-way-i-see-it-mw0000795539 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Sound engineering ===\n''The Way I See It'' was engineered by Saadiq, [[Gerry Brown]], James Tanksley, and Brungardt, who mixed the album with Saadiq.<ref name=\"credits\"/> Saadiq and Brungardt both liked to [[Multitrack recording|layer]] multiple instruments and, prior to recording, had contemplated techniques such as [[sampling (music)|sampling]] and drum [[programming (music)|programming]]. However, they ultimately found live instrumentalists more dynamic and challenged themselves to reproduce older music productions and the Motown aesthetic of the 1960s.<ref name=\"Britton\"/> To familiarize themselves with vintage recording techniques, they studied [[Mark Lewisohn]]'s 1988 book ''[[The Complete Beatles Recording Sessions]]'',<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> books about Motown Records, and images of the label's studio personnel, setup of instruments, and [[microphone practice|microphone placement]].<ref name=\"Britton\"/> They also studied Motown [[Equalization (audio)|EQ]]s to achieve a tone they found adequate for songs' rhythm guitar parts.<ref name=\"Britton\"/> Saadiq said that he had to disregard \"about 85 to 90 percent of the new techniques ... People used to take recording very seriously. They used to wear lab coats at [[Abbey Road Studios|Abbey Road]]. So I got serious with what I was trying to do, both mentally and physically.\"<ref name=\"Farinella\"/> Brungardt said in an interview for ''[[Mix (magazine)|Mix]]'' that he abandoned the approach learned on previous records he had engineered, where \"they wanted it clean with no distortion. I was taught to make sure it was polish, polish, polish, and to make sure everything fits right, the bass hits and things are clean for the big [[pop music|pop]] vocal.\"<ref name=\"Farinella\"/>\n\n[[File:SSL9000J opposite side.JPG|right|thumb|Saadiq's recording studio featured an SSL 9000 [[mixing console]] (pictured).]]\n\nSaadiq's studio integrated modern equipment such as a [[Pro Tools]] [[digital audio workstation|digital workstation]] and an [[Solid State Logic|SSL 9000]] mixing console, and featured various vintage gear, including Saadiq's 1960s [[Ludwig-Musser|Ludwig]] [[drum kit]] and a [[Drum kit#Microphones|kick-drum mic]] purchased from Abbey Road Studios.<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> In the studio, Saadiq and Brungardt experimented with techniques and equipment.<ref name=\"Britton\"/> They wanted the songs to have slower [[wikt:attack#Noun|attacks]] like older recordings, as producers in the past did not have advanced [[dynamic range compression|compressors]],<ref name=\"Britton\"/> audio tools that manipulate the [[dynamic range|dynamic content]] of [[audio signal|signals]] and affect certain sounds in a recording's mix.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shambro |first=Joe |url=http://homerecording.about.com/od/homestudiobasics/g/def_compressor.htm |title=Home Recording Glossary: Compressor (Audio Compression) |publisher=[[About.com]]. [[The New York Times Company]] |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AphAzqdX?url=http://homerecording.about.com/od/homestudiobasics/g/def_compressor.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Their production applied [[valve audio amplifier|tube preamps]] and [[vacuum tube|tube]] compressors,<ref name=\"Britton\"/> with the former used as a [[front and back ends|front end]] for Pro Tools.<ref name=\"Buskin\"/>\n\n{{quote box|quoted = 1|quote=It became almost like a bet with some of the guys who were saying, 'You can\u2019t really re-create this old-sounding stuff because the power-flow back then was different, or the way this worked or that worked was different.' So Raphael and I just locked ourselves in the studio and tried ''everything''.|source=\u2014 Charles Brungart (2011)<ref name=\"Britton\"/>|width=21%|align=left|style=padding:8px;|border=1px}}\n\nTo record vocals for the album, Saadiq used a [[Shure SM57]] [[dynamic microphone]] to thicken and distort his voice and embellish his characteristically clean delivery, while Brungardt employed a compressor and a Pro Tools [[plug-in (computing)|plug-in]] during the mix. Saadiq sought a certain \"edge\" for his vocals and an unpolished sonic element for the album.<ref name=\"Farinella\"/> They also tried to record tracks onto cassette tapes in order to produce a grittier, older sound.<ref name=\"Britton\"/> Brungardt used a FilterBank plug-in when mixing the album to uncompress vocals and roll off [[High-end audio|high-end]] sound from tracks.<ref name=\"Farinella\"/>\n\nAlthough they wanted to reproduce an older sound, Saadiq and Brunghardt also wanted to capture more of the bass and drum parts to add a louder, modern element to the mix.<ref name=\"Britton\"/><ref name=\"Farinella\"/> They applied a more basic approach to miking the instruments and utilizing the [[outboard gear]], using a [[U 47|Neumann U 47]] for guitars, alternating [[overhead microphone]]s for Saadiq's drum kit, a combination of dynamic and [[condenser microphone|condenser]] mics for the kit's [[bass drum]], and [[Ampex]] [[tape recorder|tape machine]]s for extra [[Comparison of analog and digital recording#Analog warmth|warmth]] to the kit. Brungardt used various standard mics for the [[snare drum]] to achieve a more solid cracking sound,<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> rather than capturing the drum's overall tone. Their miking of the guitars' amps was adapted from ''The Complete Beatles Recording Sessions'', and as Brungardt recounted, \"It really gave us warmth and character. It allowed the amp to breathe and we got the tones of the amp along with the room. For me, that really opened things up so that I could play with the live room, using different [[reverberation|reverbs]] to get a sound.\" For Saadiq's bass, they used a [[DI unit]] to connect a microphone [[preamplifier]], increased the [[Gain (electronics)|gain]] on a plug-in for less compression, and adjusted the low-end tones with an equalizer plug-in.<ref name=\"Farinella\"/>\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n[[File:Hitsville USA.jpg|right|thumb|''The Way I See It'' draws on the music of 1960s Motown ([[Hitsville U.S.A.|former headquarters]] pictured).]]\n\n''The Way I See It'' has a traditional soul style fashioned after the 1960s [[Motown#Motown Sound|Motown Sound]] and [[Philadelphia soul]].<ref name=\"Mulvey\">{{cite journal|last=Mulvey|first=John|title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 The Way I See It|journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|location=London|date=May 2009|page=97}}</ref> It is a departure from Saadiq's previous work with [[neo soul]],<ref name=\"Pareles\"/> which bears a [[hip hop music|hip hop]] influence.<ref name=\"Whelan\"/> J. Gabriel Boylan of ''[[The New York Observer]]'' said that Saadiq expands further beyond his work as a producer for other recording artists, for whom he encouraged a \"classic aesthetic, heavy on organic sounds and light on studio magic, deeply indebted to the past and distrustful of easy formulas\".<ref name=\"Boylan\">{{cite news|last=Boylan |first=J. Gabriel |date=September 2008 |url=http://observer.com/2008/09/who-will-save-rb/ |title=Who Will Save R&B? |newspaper=[[The New York Observer]] |accessdate=September 18, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AphJYjJE?url=http://observer.com/2008/09/who-will-save-rb/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[BBC Music]]'s Chris Jones interpreted Saadiq's use of 1960s soul as the album's source material to be a reflection of \"America's most recent great political and cultural shift ... the first true post-[[Barack Obama|Obama]] expression of hope in record form.\"<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite web|last=Jones |first=Chris |date=February 27, 2009 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/pz4h |title=Review of Raphael Saadiq \u2013 The Way I See It |publisher=[[BBC Music]]. [[BBC]] |accessdate=September 18, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AphDrF9e?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/pz4h |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saadiq viewed his rootsy direction as a response to the state of popular music and found it analogous to modern politics: \"You force so many terrible things on people, they get tired of it. We have a black president now.\"<ref name=\"Whelan\"/>\n\nThe album's songs draw on Motown's [[groove (music)|groove]]s,<ref name=\"Gill\">{{cite news|last=Gill |first=Andy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-raphael-saadiq-the-way-i-see-it-columbia-1633101.html |title=Album: Raphael Saadiq, The Way I See It (Columbia) |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=February 27, 2009 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6A2YMrxqR?url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-raphael-saadiq-the-way-i-see-it-columbia-1633101.html |archivedate=August 19, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> driving rhythms,<ref name=\"Yates\">{{cite news|last=Yates |first=Steve |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/15/raphael-saadiq-way-i-see-it |title=Urban review: Raphael Saadiq, The Way I See It |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |location=London |at=Observer Music Monthly section, p. 51 |date=February 14, 2009 |accessdate=April 3, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AphM3Uhj?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/feb/15/raphael-saadiq-way-i-see-it |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> tight drumming, tambourines in the rhythm section,<ref name=\"Deusner\">{{cite web|last=Deusner |first=Stephen M. |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12301-the-way-i-see-it/ |title=Raphael Saadiq: The Way I See It |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=October 22, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AphOuevv?url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12301-the-way-i-see-it/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> guitar melodies, layered vocal arrangements,<ref name=\"Norton\">{{cite journal |last=Norton |first=Maiya |url=http://www.vibe.com/music/revolutions/2008/09/raphael_saadiq_the_way_i_see_it/ |title=Raphael Saadiq: \"The Way I See It\" |journal=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |location=New York |date=September 17, 2008 |accessdate=April 3, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66elhyM6m?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080920021148/http://www.vibe.com/music/revolutions/2008/09/raphael_saadiq_the_way_i_see_it/ |archivedate=2012-04-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and two- to four-minute durations.<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> They also feature bright melodies, [[Swing (jazz performance style)|swinging]] bass, sweeping strings,<ref name=\"Danton\">{{cite news|last=Danton |first=Eric R. |url=http://articles.courant.com/2008-09-16/features/topcd0916.art_1_soul-sharon-jones-motown |title=Raphael Saadiq Tips His Hat To Classic Soul With 'Way I See It' |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=September 16, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AphYMtjO?url=http://articles.courant.com/2008-09-16/features/topcd0916.art_1_soul-sharon-jones-motown |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and snare drums that emit reverb.<ref name=\"Whelan\">{{cite news|last=Whelan |first=Robbie |date=March 18, 2009 |url=http://www2.citypaper.com/eat/story.asp?id=17720 |title=Guiding Lights: Raphael Saadiq looks back to the days of suit-and-tie R&B |newspaper=[[Baltimore City Paper]] |accessdate=September 18, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AphgWMeq?url=http://www2.citypaper.com/eat/story.asp?id=17720 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cameron Carrus of ''[[The Lawrentian]]'' said that the most hook-oriented riffs are played on the bass and guitar, which blend \"the low with the high\", and cited \"Keep Marchin{{'}}\", \"Love That Girl\", and \"Staying in Love\" as examples.<ref name=\"Carrus\">{{cite news |last=Carrus |first=Cameron |date=October 7, 2011 |url=http://www.lawrentian.com/arts-entertainment/raphael-saadiq-s-new-take-on-old-people-music-1.2629495 |title=Raphael Saadiq\u2019s new take on \"old people music\" |newspaper=[[The Lawrentian]] |location=Appleton |accessdate=September 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AphjaAjo?url=http://www.lawrentian.com/arts-entertainment/raphael-saadiq-s-new-take-on-old-people-music-1.2629495 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Jon Pareles]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' viewed that Saadiq follows the example of 1960s Motown artists such as [[Marvin Gaye]], [[Smokey Robinson]], Stevie Wonder, and [[Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland]], the label's songwriting and production team.<ref name=\"Pareles\">{{cite news |last=Pareles |first=Jon |authorlink=Jon Pareles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/07/arts/music/07wpoplist.html?adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1348193791-1LAeE29GCPrRPgoY8nXNZQ |title=Some Chartmakers to Be: Metal Gods and Idols Past |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=AR62 |date=September 7, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aphtdnr7?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/07/arts/music/07wpoplist.html?adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1348193791-1LAeE29GCPrRPgoY8nXNZQ&_r=0 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] wrote that the album shares Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland's \"bright, swift, clearly [[hook (music)|hooked]] aesthetic\".<ref name=\"Christgau1\">{{cite journal|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bl/saadiq-08.php|title=Raphael Saadiq: The Way I See It|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|date=October 2008|accessdate=March 30, 2012}}</ref> Saadiq sings in a [[tenor]] voice,<ref name=\"Hermes\">{{cite journal |last=Hermes |first=Will |authorlink=Will Hermes |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/raphaelsaadiq/albums/album/22955163/review/23589128/the_way_i_see_it |title=Raphael Saadiq: The Way I See It |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |date=October 30, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66Yxfae9Y?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090114090158/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/raphaelsaadiq/albums/album/22955163/review/23589128/the_way_i_see_it |archivedate=March 31, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which is slightly distorted as a result of the album's post-production.<ref name=\"Farinella\"/>\n\nSaadiq's songwriting is characterized by straightforward romanticism,<ref name=\"Varine\"/> positive exhortations, pining ballads,<ref name=\"Danton\"/> and [[protest song|message songs]].<ref name=\"Boylan\"/> Christgau interpreted Saadiq's persona on the album to be \"a romantic who stays true to the deliberate simplicity\" of the song titles, but \"never threatens to assume the fetal position if he doesn't get the extreme cuddling he craves.\"<ref name=\"Christgau1\"/> Patrick Varine of the ''[[Observer-Dispatch]]'' asserted that Saadiq deviates significantly from contemporary R&B lyrics: \"there are no thinly-veiled food-sex metaphors or pimp fantasies\".<ref name=\"Varine\">{{cite news |last=Varine |first=Patrick |date=October 1, 2008 |url=http://www.uticaod.com/ghs/features/x506588160/Album-review-The-Way-I-See-It-by-Raphael-Saadiq |title=Album review: 'The Way I See It,' by Raphael Saadiq |newspaper=[[Observer-Dispatch]] |location=Utica |accessdate=June 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApiGlUMW?url=http://www.uticaod.com/ghs/features/x506588160/Album-review-The-Way-I-See-It-by-Raphael-Saadiq |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His songwriting also paraphrases classic soul lyrics and,<ref name=\"Capobianco\">{{cite news |last=Capobianco |first=Ken |url=http://articles.boston.com/2008-09-23/ae/29278537_1_soul-raphael-saadiq-joss-stone |title=This is how you do soul |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=September 23, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApiEGJVn?url=http://articles.boston.com/2008-09-23/ae/29278537_1_soul-raphael-saadiq-joss-stone |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> on the album's slower songs, expresses tightly coiled emotions.<ref name=\"Danton\"/> Saadiq said that some songs were written about his life experiences.<ref name=\"Nathan\"/> He described the album as \"basically a series of love songs about music, how falling in love can be easy, but staying true to it can be tricky.\" He elaborated on this interpretation in an interview for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'': \"You have to watch out for those curves. [[wikt:trend#Noun|Trendy]] music comes out, and how do you stay true to what you love? I\u2019m not saying everything has to sound like a '60s record to stay true, but you should never take the relationship lightly.\"<ref name=\"Kot\"/>\n\n=== Songs ===\nThe opening track, \"Sure Hope You Mean It\", features slightly off-beat percussion, tambourine shakes,<ref name=\"Deusner\"/> and lyrics about a man who awaits a sign of approval from the woman he admires.<ref name=\"Tucker\">{{cite episode|last1=Bianculli|first1=David|last2=Tucker|first2=Ken|authorlink2=Ken Tucker|url=https://www.npr.org/player/v2/mediaPlayer.html?action=1&t=1&islist=false&id=95597193&m=95600117|title=Saadiq Revisits R&B Past In 'The Way I See It'|series=[[Fresh Air]]|network=[[NPR]]|station=[[WHYY-FM]]|location=Philadelphia|date=October 10, 2008|transcript=Transcript|transcripturl=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=95597193|accessdate=April 7, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101040011/http://www.npr.org/player/v2/mediaPlayer.html?action=1&t=1&islist=false&id=95597193&m=95600117|archivedate=January 1, 2015}}</ref> \"Keep Marchin{{'}}\", which evoked socially conscious and positive sentiments,<ref>{{cite news|date=October 2, 2008|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CO&s_site=charlotte&p_multi=CO&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1239723510678238&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=For Saadiq, Old-School Soul Runs Deep, Musician's Third Solo CD Channels '60 and '70s Doo-Wop, Beach Music and Motown|at=Style section, p. 6E|newspaper=[[Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> was composed in the vein of the [[Civil Rights Movement]] era soul music by artists such as [[Sam Cooke]] and [[the Staple Singers]].<ref name=\"Fawcett\">{{cite news|last=Fawcett |first=Thomas |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2008-10-24/693632/ |title=Raphael Saadiq |newspaper=[[The Austin Chronicle]] |date=October 24, 2012 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AOUeYQPQ?url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2008-10-24/693632/ |archivedate=September  3, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gail Mitchell from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' compared the song to [[Curtis Mayfield]] and [[the Impressions]]' 1968 song \"[[We're a Winner]]\".<ref name=\"Mitchell\">{{cite journal|last=Mitchell |first=Gail |url=http://www.billboard.com/news/the-way-i-see-it-1003852604.story |title=The Way I See It |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media]] |volume=120 |issue=39 |date=September 27, 2008 |accessdate=April 3, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApipNYN3?url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3i4bd22674ba7598a8b5d6aed3c7857031 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saadiq said \"Keep Marchin{{'}}\" was also inspired by his journey in the music industry.<ref name=\"Kot\"/>\n\n{{Listen|pos = left\n |filename     = Raphael Saadiq Big Easy.ogg\n |title        = \"Big Easy\"\n |description  = \"Big Easy\"'s tragic theme of losing a lover to [[Hurricane Katrina]] is juxtaposed with upbeat music, which Saadiq felt would evoke the spirit of New Orleans' [[jazz funeral]]s.<ref name=\"Norris\">{{cite episode|last1=Norris|first1=Michele|authorlink1=Michele Norris|last2=Siegel|first2=Robert|authorlink2=Robert Siegel|url=https://www.npr.org/player/v2/mediaPlayer.html?action=1&t=1&islist=false&id=101876552&m=101895787|title=Raphael Saadiq Brings Back the Love Song|series=[[All Things Considered]]|network=NPR|date=March 13, 2009|transcript=Transcript|transcripturl=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=101876552|accessdate=April 7, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607000206/http://www.npr.org/player/v2/mediaPlayer.html?action=1&t=1&islist=false&id=101876552&m=101895787|archivedate=June 7, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\"Big Easy\", featuring [[music of New Orleans|New Orleans]]-style [[Brass instrument|brass]] playing,<ref name=\"Hermes\"/> was sung from the point of view of a man in New Orleans who reacts to [[Hurricane Katrina]] and looks for his lost lover.<ref name=\"Rigoulet\">{{cite journal |last=Rigoulet |first=Laurent |date=June 12, 2008 |url=http://www.telerama.fr/musiques/raphael-saadiq-the-way-i-see-it,36494.php |title=Raphael Saadiq. The way I see it |journal=[[T\u00e9l\u00e9rama]] |issue=3073 |language=French |accessdate=June 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Apixtpbv?url=http://www.telerama.fr/musiques/raphael-saadiq-the-way-i-see-it,36494.php |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> J. Gabriel Boylan of ''[[The New York Observer]]'' remarked that the song \"manages to cast Hurricane Katrina as the villain in a romance, tearing lovers apart.\"<ref name=\"Boylan\"/> Its composition\u2014mixing a blissful sound with disheartening lyrics\u2014is similar to the songwriting technique used by Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland.<ref name=\"Kellman\"/> Saadiq was inspired to write \"Big Easy\" after watching the 2006 documentary film ''[[When the Levees Broke]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101876552 |title=Raphael Saadiq Brings Back the Love Song |publisher=NPR |date=March 13, 2009 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Apj2h3XT?url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101876552 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He explained its upbeat composition in an interview for ''[[All Things Considered]]'': \"In New Orleans, when they mourn, they really celebrate and have a great time. I wanted to give it that same spirit.\"<ref name=\"Norris\"/>\n\n{{Listen|pos = right\n |filename     = Raphael Saadiq Sometimes.ogg\n |title        = \"Sometimes\"\n |description  = \"Sometimes\", a tribute to both Saadiq's mother and his own perseverance,<ref>{{cite web|author=Reding, Mike |date=December 15, 2008 |url=http://www.pajiba.com/music/the-year-in-review-part-1.php |title=The Year In Review Part 1 |publisher=Pajiba |accessdate=September 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Apj5QcvK?url=http://www.pajiba.com/music/the-year-in-review-part-1.php |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live |display-authors=etal }}</ref> incorporates a contemporary musical element\u2014pulsating digital sounds\u2014in its lush [[string section|string arrangements]].<ref name=\"Meagher\">{{cite news|last=Meagher |first=John |date=May 1, 2009 |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/albums-raphael-saadiq-1725698.html |title=Albums: Raphael Saadiq **** |newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] |location=Dublin |accessdate=September 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Apjb1kvM?url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/albums-raphael-saadiq-1725698.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\nAccording to Saadiq, \"Just One Kiss\" can be interpreted as a song devoted to a female love interest, \"but I'm really talking about music and what it did for me. That one guitar line, that certain drum beat, how it turned my life into a ball of gold.\"<ref name=\"Kot\"/> The song incorporates cinematic strings,<ref name=\"Stewart\">{{cite journal|last=Stewart |first=Addi |url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/music/story.cfm?content=165287 |title=Raphael Saadiq |journal=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |location=Toronto |date=October 8, 2008 |volume=28 |issue=6 |accessdate=April 3, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Apj88F9S?url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/music/story.cfm?content=165287 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> xylophone,<ref name=\"Whelan\"/> and a rolling [[Dynamics (music)#Gradual changes|crescendo]].<ref name=\"Lewis\"/> The ballad \"Calling\", featuring Mexican balladeer Rocio Mendoza,<ref name=\"Hermes\"/> draws on Motown's late 1950s R&B roots and [[doo-wop]] music,<ref name=\"Gill\"/> and incorporates [[Latin American music|Latin]] style guitar,<ref>{{cite web|last=Nero |first=Mark Edward |url=http://randb.about.com/od/reviews/fr/SaadiqWayISeeIt.htm |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 \"The Way I See It\" |publisher=About.com. The New York Times Company |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApjMPCRE?url=http://randb.about.com/od/reviews/fr/SaadiqWayISeeIt.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Spanish language]] lyrics.<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> \"Staying in Love\", an uptempo rhythm and blues song,<ref>{{cite web|author=Dantana |url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/Audio-Raphael-Saadiq-Staying-In-Love.html |title=Audio: Raphael Saadiq \"Staying In Love\" |publisher=Okayplayer |date=August 11, 2008 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApjO3Pdp?url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/Audio-Raphael-Saadiq-Staying-In-Love.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> was written by Saadiq after he thought of an ex-girlfriend.<ref name=\"Nathan\"/> Incongruous with its 1960s-inspired sound,<ref name=\"Wikane\">{{cite web|last=Wikane |first=Christian John |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/raphael-saadiq-the-way-i-see-it |title=Raphael Saadiq: The Way I See It |work=[[PopMatters]] |date=September 18, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Apiu6pdf?url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/raphael-saadiq-the-way-i-see-it |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"Let's Take a Walk\" has sexually forward lyrics and [[wikt:come on#Noun|come-ons]],<ref name=\"Hermes\"/> which the narrator uses to bluntly proposition his love interest.<ref name=\"Fawcett\"/> The midtempo \"Never Give You Up\" is fashioned in Motown's early 1970 sound and,<ref name=\"Lewis\"/> unlike other songs on the album, also incorporates elements from more modern soul music.<ref name=\"Mays\">{{cite news|last=May|first=Mark|date=September 25, 2008|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/tennessean/access/1696863521.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+25%2C+2008&author=MARK+MAYS&pub=The+Tennessean&desc=Raphael+Saadiq%2C+The+Way+I+See+It&pqatl=google|title=Raphael Saadiq, The Way I See It|newspaper=[[The Tennessean]]|at=Tune In section|accessdate=June 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Sometimes\" was inspired by Saadiq's upbringing in a tough neighborhood in [[Oakland]],<ref name=\"Candace\"/> and is about dealing with the fatigue of universal hardships when they are worsened by the burden of racism.<ref name=\"Boylan\"/> The line \"now I know what they meant by '[[Keep Your Head to the Sky|keep your head to the sky]]'\" makes reference to [[Earth, Wind & Fire]], whose music Saadiq immersed himself in while growing up.<ref name=\"Candace\"/> Saadiq said of the song's message, \"That's just giving dap to my moms and grandmother and the people who raised me in the neighborhood to let them know its easy but not as easy as it seems all the time and sometimes we have to back up and cry but I'm just giving thanks to the people that helped me along the way.\"<ref name=\"Coachman\">{{cite web |last=Coachman |first=Dale |url=http://www.clutchmagonline.com/2008/09/raphael-saadiq-world-soul/ |title=Raphael Saadiq: World Soul |publisher=Clutch Magazine. Sutton New Media LLC |date=September 1, 2008 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApieVabv?url=http://www.clutchmagonline.com/2008/09/raphael-saadiq-world-soul/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Title and packaging ==\n[[File:The Temptations 1968.JPG|thumb|right|According to ''[[PopMatters]]'', the cover shows Saadiq dressed as \"a veritable one-man [[Temptations]]\" (the group pictured above, in 1968), \"mirroring the lithe physique and bespectacled eyes of [[David Ruffin]]\" (far left).<ref name=\"Wikane\"/>]]\n\nSaadiq titled ''The Way I See It'' as a declaration to listeners about how his perspective was more informed by classic soul than before in his career. \"This is what I really love\", he later explained. \"And everything you've heard from me before has been based on the roots of this music.\"<ref name=\"Lewis\"/> \n\nThe cover photo was taken at a show in 2006 at Sweet's Ballroom in Oakland, in which Saadiq performed Marvin Gaye's 1965 song \"[[Ain't That Peculiar]]\".<ref name=\"Powers\"/> It showed Saadiq singing into a microphone with his arms raised and wearing a suit, tie,<ref name=\"Kot\"/> and thick-rimmed glasses: a look similar to that of Temptations singer [[David Ruffin]].<ref name=\"Norton\"/> According to Saadiq, the photo \"set the tone for the whole album ... me singing that song, me wearing that suit, it said everything that this album should be.\"<ref name=\"Kot\"/> Music journalist [[Greg Kot]] believed the cover \"evokes the dramatic portraits and color schemes of old-school jazz and soul albums. Think [[Ray Charles]] on [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], [[Sonny Rollins]] on [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], [[Sam & Dave|Sam and Dave]] on Stax ... With arms raised, he looks like he's testifying as much as singing.\"<ref name=\"Kot\"/> The rest of the album's packaging also adheres to a retro aesthetic with its crimson-tinted cover's font and 1960s Columbia Records logo.<ref name=\"Norton\"/><ref name=\"Stewart\"/><ref name=\"Wikane\"/> The packaging's photography was taken by [[Norman Seeff]].<ref name=\"credits\"/>\n\n== Marketing and sales ==\nBefore completing ''The Way I See It'', Saadiq previewed its songs in May 2008 to music industry associates and journalists at the Sony Club in New York City.<ref name=\"Candace\"/> He also planned a grassroots marketing strategy for the record, which evolved from his difficulty with Columbia executives to promote the album and their idea of issuing its songs as [[gramophone record|vinyl records]]. He felt that \"nobody at the label knew\" him in an interview with ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'': \"They had this record that I turned in that sounded like a '60s record. 'What the hell do we do with this record?' It was quality. There was not a lot of marketing and promotion, but they knew I had the credibility so you don't just throw it in the garbage ... I don't mind being a [[wikt:slow burn|slow burn]] because that's actually a better road to take. I have to go in one more time and prove myself again because I am starting over again.\"<ref name=\"Tarradell\">{{cite news|last=Tarradell |first=Mario |date=November 25, 2009 |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/entertainment/columnists/mario-tarradell/20091124-Raphael-Saadiq-brings-his-soulful-manifesto-526.ece |title=Raphael Saadiq brings his soulful manifesto to Dallas |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |accessdate=May 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmOWjia?url=http://www.dallasnews.com/entertainment/columnists/mario-tarradell/20091124-Raphael-Saadiq-brings-his-soulful-manifesto-526.ece |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, Columbia released the album both on CD and as a collector's edition [[box set]] with 7-inch vinyl singles.<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> In the United Kingdom, it was issued with two bonus tracks\u2014a \"Euro version\" of \"Big Easy\" and the song \"Come On Home\".<ref name=\"Kuenzler\">{{cite web|last=Kuenzler|first=Hanspeter|date=February 2009|url=http://www.musicomh.com/albums/raphael-saadiq_0209.htm|title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 The Way I See It|work=[[musicOMH]]|accessdate=April 9, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302073951/http://www.musicomh.com/albums/raphael-saadiq_0209.htm|archivedate=March 2, 2009}}</ref> In the week leading up to the album's release, Saadiq made promotional appearances at [[WVEE|V-103]]'s For Sisters Only, the International Soul Music Summit, and the Uptown Restaurant & Lounge in Atlanta.<ref>{{cite news |last=Caramanica |first=Jon |date=September 16, 2008 |url=http://www.accessatlanta.com/music/content/music/cds/stories//2008/09/16/Darius_Rucker_cd.html |title=Darius Rucker: \u2018Learn To Live\u2019 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=June 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AOURgDUC?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20081205084445/http://www.accessatlanta.com/music/content/music/cds/stories//2008/09/16/Darius_Rucker_cd.html |archivedate=2012-09-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He also performed songs from the album on ''[[VH1 Soul]]stage''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/nme-video/youtube/id/i2In15qfs9k |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 100 Yard Dash, Calling You (Live on SoulStage 2008) video |work=[[NME]] |accessdate=September 17, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AplDVBg9?url=http://www.nme.com/nme-video/youtube/id/i2In15qfs9k |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\n''The Way I See It'' was largely overlooked by consumers at first.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Watson |first=Margeaux |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2008/12/24/raphael-saadiqs/ |title=Raphael Saadiq's 'The Way I See It': Most overlooked CD of the year |journal=Entertainment Weekly |location=New York |date=December 24, 2008 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmCYKyM?url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2008/12/24/raphael-saadiqs/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The album debuted at number 19 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, selling 23,000 copies in the week of October 4.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Caufield |first=Keith |date=September 24, 2008 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043994/metallica-edges-ne-yo-nelly-to-remain-no-1 |title=Metallica Edges Ne-Yo, Nelly To Remain No. 1 |journal=Billboard |volume=120 |issue=41 |accessdate=May 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmJf98c?url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/news/e3i7e27e06b2dc44448226e6fa985660ce9 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nonetheless, it was Saadiq's highest-charting album in the United States at the time,<ref name=\"bbSaadiq\"/> and by November, had steadily sold 76,919 copies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Paine |first=Jake |date=November 19, 2008 |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.8116/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-11-17-08 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 11/17/08 |publisher=HipHop DX. Cheri Media Group |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmLrqDm?url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.8116/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-11-17-08 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Five [[single (music)|singles]] were released from the album\u2014\"Love That Girl\" on August 5, 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=8748842 |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 Love That Girl MP3 Download |publisher=[[CD Universe]] |accessdate=May 20, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AplaKsJi?url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=8748842 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"100 Yard Dash\" on March 30, 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Raphael+Saadiq&titel=100+Yard+Dash&cat=s |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 100 Yard Dash |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=September 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aplznksv?url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Raphael+Saadiq&titel=100+Yard+Dash&cat=s |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"Never Give You Up\" on May 27,<ref>{{cite web|last=Nero |first=Mark Edward |date=May 27, 2009 |url=http://randb.about.com/b/2009/05/27/raphael-saadiq-never-give-you-up.htm |title=Raphael Saadiq will 'Never Give You Up' |publisher=About.com. The New York Times Company |accessdate=September 18, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqjQ8fwk?url=http://randb.about.com/b/2009/05/27/raphael-saadiq-never-give-you-up.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"Let's Take a Walk\" on August 7,<ref>{{cite web|last=Cadet |first=Thierry |date=August 7, 2012 |url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Raphael-Saadiq/news-68352.html |title=D\u00e9couvrez le nouveau clip de Raphael Saadiq |publisher=Pure Charts |language=French |accessdate=September 18, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqjSSgRl?url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Raphael-Saadiq/news-68352.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and \"Staying in Love\" on October 5.<ref name=\"Oct5\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/10/06/idUS11198+06-Oct-2009+PRN20091006 |title=Grammy(R) Award Winning Singer-Songwriter Raphael Saadiq Closes Out 2009 With Kings Keep Marchin' Tour |agency=[[PR Newswire]] |location=New York |date=October 5, 2009 |accessdate=September 18, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqkabQqh?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/10/06/idUS11198+06-Oct-2009+PRN20091006 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"Love That Girl\", \"Never Give You Up\", and \"Staying in Love\" all charted on the US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]], peaking at number 45, number 26, and number 74, respectively.<ref name=\"bbsongs\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=raphael saadiq|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Songs}}|title=Raphael Saadiq Album & Song Chart History|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2009, Saadiq travelled for promotional television appearances and press in Europe,<ref name=\"Graff\"/> where ''The Way I See It'' had charted in several countries.<ref name=\"Hung Medien\">{{cite web |url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Raphael+Saadiq&titel=The+Way+I+See+It&cat=a |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 The Way I See It |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=September 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmVsyul?url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Raphael+Saadiq&titel=The+Way+I+See+It&cat=a |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In France, the record spent 51 weeks on the country's albums chart, peaking at number 13 in the week of February 24.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cadet |first=Thierry |date=February 24, 2009 |url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Mylene-Farmer/news-67567.html |title=Tops : Myl\u00e8ne Farmer obtient son septi\u00e8me n\u00b01 |publisher=[[PureM\u00e9dias|Pure Charts by Charts in France]]. Web\u00e9dia |language=French |accessdate=June 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AsqC2slP?url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Mylene-Farmer/news-67567.html |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In August, it re-entered the American chart at number 101 and had sold 215,000 copies.<ref>{{cite journal|last=George|first=Raphael|date=August 8, 2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lCUF-Ml_lBYC&pg=PT41#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Saadiq Finds His 'Way' Up Chart|journal=Billboard|page=42|accessdate=September 14, 2012|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> The album charted for 41 weeks on the ''Billboard'' 200, serving as the longest chart-run of Saadiq's career.<ref name=\"bbSaadiq\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=raphael saadiq|chart=Billboard 200}} |title=Raphael Saadiq Album & Song Chart History |work=Billboard |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923150541/http://www.cmc.dk/ |archivedate=September 23, 2010 }}</ref> By May 2011, it had sold 282,000 copies, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Gardner |first=Elysa |date=May 10, 2011 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2011-05-10-saadiq_st_N.htm |title=Things are 'Rollin\" for Raphael Saadiq |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |location=New York |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmT9KJv?url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2011-05-10-saadiq_st_N.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 7.2/10<ref name=\"ADM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/1019/Raphael-Saadiq-The-Way-I-See-It.aspx|title=The Way I See It by Raphael Saadiq|work=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n| MC = 79/100<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Kellman\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Christgau1\"/>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A<ref name=\"Watson\">{{cite journal |last=Watson |first=Margeaux |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20226350,00.html |title=The Way I See It Review |journal=Entertainment Weekly |location=New York |issue=1013 |date=September 26, 2008 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmgA8kZ?url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20226350,00.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Sullivan\"/>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Gill\"/>\n| rev6 = ''[[MSN Music]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Consumer Guide]])\n| rev6Score = A<ref name=\"Christgau2\">{{cite web|last=Christgau |first=Robert |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg2008-10.php |title=Inside Music: Consumer Guide |work=[[MSN Music]] |date=October 2008 |accessdate=April 28, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Api8FEvF?url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg2008-10.php |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 6.8/10<ref name=\"Deusner\"/>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Qmag\"/>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Hermes\"/>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Mulvey\"/>\n}}\n''The Way I See It'' was met with generally positive reviews. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 79, based on 20 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-way-i-see-it |title=The Way I See It Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More |publisher=[[Metacritic]]. [[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AsqbRbxX?url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-way-i-see-it |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave it 7.2 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"ADM\"/>\n\nReviewing the album for ''[[The Guardian]]'' in April 2009, Caroline Sullivan called it flawlessly produced and performed by Saadiq,<ref name=\"Sullivan\">{{cite news|last=Sullivan |first=Caroline |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/24/raphael-saadiq-review |title=Urban review: Raphal Saadiq: The Way I See It |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |at=Film & Music section, p. 11 |date=April 23, 2009 |accessdate=April 2, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApjIbWby?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/apr/24/raphael-saadiq-review |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> while ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's [[Will Hermes]] said the record showcased an original take on classic [[Northern soul]].<ref name=\"Hermes\"/> Andy Gill of ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote that it was one of 2008's most captivating albums because \"few have managed to retro-fabricate that classic sound so accurately, nor in as many subtle variations\" like Saadiq.<ref name=\"Gill\"/> [[AllMusic]]'s Andy Kellman stated, \"Here's where a modern master, backed by living and breathing session musicians ... masters the masters with startling accuracy.\"<ref name=\"Kellman\"/> In ''[[The Observer]]'', [[Kitty Empire]] found the album \"both feather-light and substantial\" because of how, \"unlike most modern records, Saadiq's tunes gather weight the deeper in you go\".<ref name=\"Empire\">{{cite news|last=Empire |first=Kitty |authorlink=Kitty Empire |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/01/motown-raphael-saadiq-album-review |title=Urban review: Raphael Saadiq, The Way I See It |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |at=Observer Review section, p. 18 |date=February 28, 2009 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApjVTDoX?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/mar/01/motown-raphael-saadiq-album-review |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''[[MSN Music]]'', Christgau said Saadiq sang with Smokey Robinson's detailed sentimentality and [[Dennis Edwards]]' amenable personality.<ref name=\"Christgau2\"/> He expanded on his praise in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', finding that, while \"painstakingly retro\", Saadiq's achievement \"isn't replicating the Motown Sound but writing consistently charming and catchy songs in that style\".<ref name=\"ChristgauSlate\">{{cite journal|last=Christgau |first=Robert |date=December 18, 2008 |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/the_music_club/features/2008/the_music_club/my_lists.html |title=My Lists |journal=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmnM7UP?url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/the_music_club/features/2008/the_music_club/my_lists.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' was more critical, finding the record devoid of a \"fresh approach\" to elevate it from a simple homage.<ref name=\"Qmag\">{{cite journal|title=Review: The Way I See It|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|date=April 2009|page=110|issue=273}}</ref> According to ''[[PopMatters]]'' writer Christian John Wikane, \"one's total enjoyment of the album depends on their appreciation of classic soul and R&B and whether such appreciation is contingent on absolute authenticity.\"<ref name=\"Wikane\"/>\n\nAt the end of 2008, ''The Way I See It'' was included in a number of critics' best albums lists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metacritic.com/music/bests/2008.shtml |title=Best Albums of 2008 |publisher=Metacritic. CBS Interactive |date=December 2008 |accessdate=November 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AglqIePL?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090209033553/http://metacritic.com/music/bests/2008.shtml |archivedate=September 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was named one of the year's 10-best records by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|date=December 19, 2008 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2008/12/pop-hiss-top-te.html |title=Pop top-10 lists, and 2008's recommended albums |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqnMNEgR?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2008/12/pop-hiss-top-te.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news|last=Fusilli |first=Jim |date=December 26, 2008 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123005281362230443 |title=They Don't All Sound Familiar |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |location=New York |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aqmkuu4R?url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB123005281362230443.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'', which cited it as ninth best.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dansby |first=Andrew |date=December 30, 2008 |url=http://www.chron.com/entertainment/music/article/Year-end-best-Can-t-get-enough-of-these-CDs-1777851.php |title=Year-end best: Can't get enough of these CDs |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqnCWFAA?url=http://www.chron.com/entertainment/music/article/Year-end-best-Can-t-get-enough-of-these-CDs-1777851.php |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was also ranked at number five by ''[[Exclaim!]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|author=Cowie, Del F. el al. |date=December 2008 |url=http://exclaim.ca/Features/YearInReview/groove_year_in_review_2008 |title=Groove: Year in Review 2008 |journal=[[Exclaim!]] |location=Ontario |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aqn702L9?url=http://exclaim.ca/Features/YearInReview/groove_year_in_review_2008 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> number seven by ''[[The Irish Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Carroll |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim Carroll (journalist) |date=December 11, 2009 |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/blogs/ontherecord/2009/12/11/otrs-albums-of-the-year-and-the-decade/ |title=OTR's albums of the year \u2013 and the decade |newspaper=[[The Irish Times]] |location=Dublin |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqnFTT4G?url=http://www.irishtimes.com/blogs/ontherecord/2009/12/11/otrs-albums-of-the-year-and-the-decade/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> number one by [[NPR]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Tucker |first=Ken |date=December 16, 2008 |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98327691 |title=Year In Review: The Top Pop Of 2008 |publisher=NPR |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqnPZklT?url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98327691 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> number five by ''[[The Observer]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Empire |first=Kitty |date=December 12, 2009 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/dec/13/2009-review-pop-kitty-empire |title=2009 in review: Pop |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |at=Observer Review section, p. 10 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqnaaIiw?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/dec/13/2009-review-pop-kitty-empire |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> number three by ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 16, 2008 |url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/music-the-best-and-worst-of-2008 |title=Music: The best (and worst) of 2008 |journal=Time Out |location=New York |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqoFjlJm?url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/music-the-best-and-worst-of-2008 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and number two by ''[[USA Today]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gardner |first=Elysa |date=December 18, 2008 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2008-12-18-music-yir-top5albums_N.htm |title=Our critics' picks of 2008 |newspaper=USA Today |location=McLean |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqnzHaS8?url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2008-12-18-music-yir-top5albums_N.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Way I See It'' was voted the 18th best album of 2008 in the [[Pazz & Jop]], an annual poll of American critics nationwide, published in ''[[The Village Voice]]'';<ref name=\"PazzJop\">{{cite news|year=2008 |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/albums/2008/ |title=New York Pazz and Jop Albums |newspaper=The Village Voice |location=New York |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmpmYIj?url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/albums/2008/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> the poll's singles list had six of the album's songs voted in, including \"100 Yard Dash\" at number 114 and both \"Love That Girl\" and \"Big Easy\" at number 250.<ref>{{cite news|year=2008 |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/singles/2008/ |title=New York Pazz and Jop Singles |newspaper=The Village Voice |location=New York |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmsMr6k?url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/singles/2008/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nate Chinen of ''[[The New York Times]]'' included \"100 Yard Dash\" in his top-five singles list for 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chinen |first=Nate |date=December 21, 2008 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/21/arts/music/21chin.html |title=Standouts in Rap, Jazz and Country |newspaper=The New York Times |page=AR33 |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmuKvsB?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/21/arts/music/21chin.html?_r=0 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Way I See It'' also nominated for the [[Grammy Award|2009 Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Album|Best R&B Album]].<ref name=\"Grammy\">{{cite web|author=Gingerlynn |date=December 4, 2008 |url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/09-Grammy-Award-Nominations-Al-Green-M_I_A-Estelle-Jazmine-Sullivan-and-more.html |title=\u201909 Grammy Award Nominations: Al Green, M.I.A., Estelle, Jazmine Sullivan and more! |publisher=Okayplayer |accessdate=April 9, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqmwpInY?url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/09-Grammy-Award-Nominations-Al-Green-M_I_A-Estelle-Jazmine-Sullivan-and-more.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"Love That Girl\" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional R&B Vocal Performance|Best Traditional R&B Vocal Performance]], while \"Never Give You Up\" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals]].<ref name=\"Grammy\"/>\n\n== Touring ==\n[[File:Raphael Saadiq at Stockholm Jazz 2.jpg|left|thumb|Saadiq performing at the 2009 [[Stockholm Jazz Festival]]]]\n\nSaadiq toured for about two years to promote ''The Way I See It'',<ref name=\"Wood\">{{cite news|last=Wood |first=Mikael |date=May 15, 2011 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/may/15/entertainment/la-ca-raphael-saadiq-20110515 |title=Raphael Saadiq gets rowdy |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqlQHZFM?url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/may/15/entertainment/la-ca-raphael-saadiq-20110515 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> performing in venues throughout the United States, Europe, and Asia.<ref name=\"musique\">{{cite web |date=October 15, 2011 |url=http://www.evous.fr/Charlie-Winston-sur-le-DVD-live-de-Raphael-Saadiq,1152458.html |title=Charlie Winston sur le DVD live de Raphael Saadiq ! |publisher=Evous |language=French |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqlSPTQN?url=http://www.evous.fr/Charlie-Winston-sur-le-DVD-live-de-Raphael-Saadiq,1152458.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was originally apprehensive at the prospect of touring extensively,<ref name=\"Wood\"/> having toured minimally as a solo act.<ref name=\"Graff\">{{cite journal|last=Graff |first=Gary |date=December 19, 2008 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266072/saadiq-hits-the-road-records-with-fantasia |title=Saadiq Hits The Road, Records With Fantasia |journal=Billboard |accessdate=September 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqlYvDJB?url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/genre/news/e3id78469d811368539315240f6838d49ea |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He reconsidered at the advice of his rhythm guitarist Rob Bacon, which he recounted in an interview for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'': \"The money was just OK, so I was like, 'I don't know \u2013 I could probably stay home and find something better,' But then Rob reminded me, 'You know, all those cats you love, that's exactly what they did. [[Little Richard]]? He played 10 shows a day at the [[Apollo Theater|Apollo]].' I said, 'OK, let's go.'\"<ref name=\"Wood\"/> To complement his songs' style, Saadiq adopted a vintage soul image and, having studied footage of classic soul groups and album sleeves,<ref name=\"Lewis\"/> donned old-fashioned attire and performed R&B dance moves at shows.<ref name=\"Britton\"/><ref name=\"Herman\"/> He wore a yellow tailored suit, while his nine-piece backing band wore black suits.<ref name=\"Alstyne\">{{cite news |last=van Alstyne |first=Rob |date=March 16, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/twincities/articles/recap-raphael-saadiq-at-fine-line,25149/ |title=Recap: Raphael Saadiq at Fine Line |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]] |location=Chicago |accessdate=May 16, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6A2S5BkhR?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20091118132318/http://www.avclub.com/twincities/articles/recap-raphael-saadiq-at-fine-line,25149/ |archivedate=August 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The band included a horn section and backup singer Erika Jerry.<ref name=\"Chenin\">{{cite news |last=Chenin |first=Nate |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/30/arts/music/30sadd.html |title=Multiple Visions of Soul Music\u2019s Past and Future |newspaper=The New York Times |page=B11 |date=August 30, 2008 |accessdate=April 3, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ApjFe36q?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/30/arts/music/30sadd.html?adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1348195036-l4tvnSfbLCrgJS2QZfhgFA&_r=0 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBefore the album's release, Saadiq had toured Europe during the summer in 2008.<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> In November and December, he served as a supporting act for [[John Legend]].<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> He also opened for [[Seal (musician)|Seal]] and the [[Dave Matthews Band]].<ref name=\"Wood\"/> Throughout his touring in the US and Europe, Saadiq played various music festivals, including [[Austin City Limits Music Festival|Austin City Limits]], [[Bonnaroo Music Festival|Bonnaroo]], [[Lollapalooza]], [[South by Southwest]], [[Voodoo Experience]],<ref name=\"PR\">{{cite press release|agency=PR Newswire |location=New York |date=January 6, 2011 |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/raphael-saadiq-set-to-release-his-fifth-solo-album-stone-rollin-on-march-22-2011-112997149.html |title=Raphael Saadiq Set to Release His Fifth Solo Album Stone Rollin' on March 22, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aqlb8CKS?url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/raphael-saadiq-set-to-release-his-fifth-solo-album-stone-rollin-on-march-22-2011-112997149.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Bumbershoot]], [[Outside Lands Music and Arts Festival|Outside Lands]],<ref name=\"Britton\"/> and [[Pori Jazz]].<ref>{{cite press release |date=February 18, 2009 |url=http://www.festivals.fi/uutiset/52/ |title=Grammy-voittaja Duffy Pori Jazziin |publisher=Finland Festivals |language=Finnish |accessdate=June 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqllSw05?url=http://www.festivals.fi/uutiset/52/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In February 2009, he performed at the [[Harvard Club of Boston]] as part of the music television series ''[[Live from the Artists Den]]''.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/artists-den-and-columbia-records-to-release-live-raphael-saadiq-dvd-july-21-62087037.html |title=Artists Den and Columbia Records to Release Live Raphael Saadiq DVD July 21 |date=June 10, 2009 |agency=PR Newswire |location=New York |accessdate=April 9, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqlgiEG5?url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/artists-den-and-columbia-records-to-release-live-raphael-saadiq-dvd-july-21-62087037.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 25, he played the [[Blue Note Tokyo]] in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|author=dantana |date=June 26, 2009 |url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/Video-Raphael-Saadiq-I-Want-You-Back-Live-in-Tokyo.html |title=Video: Raphael Saadiq \"I Want You Back\" (Live in Tokyo) |publisher=Okayplayer |accessdate=April 9, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqljAS4j?url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/Video-Raphael-Saadiq-I-Want-You-Back-Live-in-Tokyo.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> His performance at the [[Bataclan (theatre)|Bataclan]] in Paris on July 11 was filmed and released as a DVD, entitled ''Live in Paris'', in 2010.<ref name=\"musique\"/> After a stretch of summer festival performances in 2009, Saadiq embarked on another leg of concerts during November and December, with [[Melanie Fiona]],<ref name=\"Tarradell\"/> [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]], and [[Anjulie]] as supporting acts.<ref>{{cite web|author=Shamz |date=October 7, 2009 |url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/Raphael-Saadiqs-Fall-Tour-Dates.html |title=Raphael Saadiq's Fall Tour Dates |publisher=Okayplayer |accessdate=April 9, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqloYdHZ?url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/Raphael-Saadiqs-Fall-Tour-Dates.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The tour featured dates in North America,<ref name=\"Oct5\"/> but Saadiq also performed at the [[Paradiso (Amsterdam)|Paradiso]] in Amsterdam on November 13.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hovenga |first=Dick |date=November 13, 2008 |url=http://www.nu.nl/muziek/1837199/raphael-saadiq----the-way-i-see-it.html |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 The Way I See It |publisher=[[NU.nl]]. [[Sanoma|Sanoma Media Group]] |language=Dutch |accessdate=May 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AqlqVqkT?url=http://www.nu.nl/muziek/1837199/raphael-saadiq----the-way-i-see-it.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He continued touring for the album into 2010, including performances at the [[JazzReggae Festival @ UCLA|JazzReggae Festival]] in May,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.sys-con.com/node/1340468 |title=Raphael Saadiq, Nas and Damian 'Jr. Gong' Marley Headline JazzReggae Festival 2010 |agency=PR Newswire |location=Los Angeles |date=March 31, 2010 |accessdate=May 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aqlutwph?url=http://www.sys-con.com/node/1340468 |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> the [[Essence Music Festival]] in July,<ref>{{cite news |last=Fensterstock |first=Alison |date=July 2, 2010 |url=http://www.nola.com/essencefest/index.ssf/2010/07/raphael_saadiq_sizzles_at_esse.html |title=Raphael Saadiq sizzles Friday at Essence Fest 2010 |newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]] |location=New Orleans |accessdate=April 10, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aqm7gRvF?url=http://www.nola.com/essencefest/index.ssf/2010/07/raphael_saadiq_sizzles_at_esse.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and a headlining performance at [[Central Park SummerStage]] in August.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williamson |first=Monica |date=August 2, 2010 |url=http://blogs.centrictv.com/music/soulsessions/soul-assessmentraphael-saadiq-and-aloe-blacc-at-nycs-summerstage/ |title=Soul Assessment//Raphael Saadiq and Aloe Blacc at NYC's Summerstage |publisher=[[BET Her|Centric]]. [[BET Networks]] |accessdate=September 19, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aqm9fble?url=http://blogs.centrictv.com/music/soulsessions/soul-assessmentraphael-saadiq-and-aloe-blacc-at-nycs-summerstage/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{quote box|quoted = 1|quote=I just wanted to get a record out there that I thought would match the world \u2013 every type of person, people all over the world from the States to Europe to Russia to everywhere. I felt like that style of music works all over the world, and I wanted to make a contribution in '08 and '09 and '10 and create something that would take me around the world.|source=\u2014 [[Raphael Saadiq]] (2008)<ref name=\"Graff\"/>|salign=right|width=21%|align=right|style=padding:8px;|border=1px}}\n\n''The Way I See It'' was an exemplary release of the classic soul revival during its peak in 2008.<ref name=\"Herman\">{{cite journal|last=Herman |first=Max |date=March 30, 2011 |url=http://illinoisentertainer.com/2011/03/interview-raphael-saadiq/ |title=Interview: Raphael Saadiq |journal=Illinois Entertainer |location=Chicago |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aqo9B6k9?url=http://illinoisentertainer.com/2011/03/interview-raphael-saadiq/ |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=December 22, 2008 |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=97798915 |title=Raphael Saadiq: Neo-Soul Producer Steps Out |publisher=NPR |accessdate=June 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ArTvezqk?url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=97798915 |archivedate=September 22, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The music scene was marked by similarly retro-minded work from mainstream artists such as [[Amy Winehouse]] and [[Adele]], independent acts such as [[Sharon Jones & the Dap-Kings]] and [[Mayer Hawthorne]], and older artists attempting comebacks such as [[Al Green]] and [[Bettye LaVette]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Herrington |first=Chris |date=October 23, 2008 |url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/reemerging-soul/Content?oid=1307586 |title=Reemerging Soul |newspaper=[[Memphis Flyer]] |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ArU124fo?url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/reemerging-soul/Content?oid=1307586 |archivedate=September 22, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sullivan |first=James |date=March 8, 2010 |url=http://www.spinner.com/2010/03/08/smokey-robinson-sxsw-soul-revue/ |title=SXSW Keynote Speaker Smokey Robinson Leads a Soul Revival in Austin |publisher=Spinner. AOL |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AsuDxg5W?url=http://www.spinner.com/2010/03/08/smokey-robinson-sxsw-soul-revue/ |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Oliver Wang cited Saadiq's album, along with [[Solange Knowles]]' 2008 record ''[[Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams]]'', as one of the \"retro-soul\" efforts that were released by contemporary R&B artists as the music scene peaked in popularity. Wang wrote that ''The Way I See It'' \"showcased a mastery of any number of past R&B styles, including those out of [[Memphis soul|Memphis]], [[Muscle Shoals Sound Studio|Muscle Shoals]], Philadelphia, [[New Orleans rhythm and blues|New Orleans]], and of course, Detroit.\"<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Weisbard|editor-first=Eric|last=Wang|first=Oliver|chapter=The Comfort Zone|title=Pop When the World Falls Apart: Music in the Shadow of Doubt|publisher=[[Duke University Press]]|year=2012|isbn=0822351080|page=221}}</ref> [[Estelle (musician)|Estelle]] said in 2008, \"Every song is like a different era of Motown ... Everything sounds exactly like it did back in the day. Not to take away from Amy, but this is the real shit.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carnwath |first1=Ally |last2=Carter |first2=Imogen |date=November 29, 2008 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/nov/30/best-albums-of-2008 |title=The best albums of 2008 \u2013 by the hot artists |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |at=Observer Review section, p. 10 |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AsuP6yta?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2008/nov/30/best-albums-of-2008 |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was described by [[David Nathan (music writer)|David Nathan]] as the \"contemporary album that was the closest to authentically recreating the great soul music sound of the late '60s and early '70s.\"<ref name=\"Nathan\"/> [[Ken Tucker]] found it distinct from other soul revival music: \"You can reproduce variations on melodies and rhythm, but without an emotional commitment, it's all tedious pandering to [[baby boomer]]s. For Raphael Saadiq, there's a glowing vibrancy in soul music that allows him to work out themes and ideas.\"<ref name=\"Tucker\"/>\n\n''The Way I See It'' also earned Saadiq the highest international profile of his career.<ref name=\"Lewis\"/> In promoting the album, he broadened his audience demographic and expanded his repertoire as a touring artist.<ref name=\"Britton\"/> His extensive touring in the US and Europe garnered the attention of younger, white audiences who were not exposed to his previous solo albums and work with Tony! Toni! Ton\u00e9!.<ref name=\"Britton\"/><ref name=\"PR\"/> ''[[The Press of Atlantic City]]'' wrote that the album \"brought in a whole new generation of Saadiq fans, with songs such as '100 Yard Dash' striking a chord with even ironic teenagers.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/life/article_d61b5b03-7283-57d5-b6cc-456c2538ac94.html |title=At the Shore Today |newspaper=[[The Press of Atlantic City]] |location=Pleasantville |date=December 5, 2009 |accessdate=May 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AsurgZzZ?url=http://m.pressofatlanticcity.com/mobile/article_d61b5b03-7283-57d5-b6cc-456c2538ac94.html |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to Gail Mitchell of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', ''The Way I See It'' helped Saadiq reach \"the major-market [[Hipster (contemporary subculture)|hipster]] crowd, music supervisors and festival bookers.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mitchell|first=Gail|date=March 19, 2011|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D0b70DQT1HkC&pg=RA8-PA41#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=It Feels Good|journal=Billboard|location=New York|page=41|volume=123|issue=9|accessdate=March 28, 2013|via=Google Books}}</ref> He also attained a following among Japanese audiences.<ref name=\"Britton\"/> Saadiq's touring for the album influenced his approach for recording his next album, ''[[Stone Rollin']]'', in 2011,<ref name=\"PR\"/> as he noted the louder, raw sound and general feeling of performing live.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Rich |date=March 23, 2011 |url=http://www.redbull.com/cs/Satellite/en_INT/Article/raphael-saadiq-talks-about-his-new-album-stone-021242980619335 |title=Raphael Saadiq- Stone Rollin |publisher=[[Red Bull GmbH]] |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AsuTz9LO?url=http://www.redbull.com/cs/Satellite/en_INT/Article/raphael-saadiq-talks-about-his-new-album-stone-021242980619335 |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> It also continued his partnership with Charles Brungart, who assisted Saadiq in recording ''Stone Rollin{{'}}''.<ref name=\"Britton\"/>\n\nSaadiq called ''The Way I See It'' \"the culmination of a lifetime of experiences informed by the music I grew up on.\"<ref name=\"Buskin\"/> Kristal Hawkins of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' said that he \"hit his artistic maturity\" with the album.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hawkins |first=Kristal |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2011-06-15/voice-choices/thievery-corporation-raphael-saadiq-dam-funk/ |title=Thievery Corporation+Raphael Saadiq+Dam-Funk |newspaper=The Village Voice |location=New York |date=June 15, 2011 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AsuXTIvu?url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2011-06-15/voice-choices/thievery-corporation-raphael-saadiq-dam-funk/%7Ctitle%3DThievery%20Corporation+Raphael%20Saadiq+Dam-Funk/ |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] remarked on its place in his solo career, \"In 1996, Saadiq turned the [[House of Music|climactic Tony! Toni! Ton\u00e9! album]] into a virtuoso history lesson. Six years later, he tried to dazzle [[Maxwell (musician)|Maxwell]] in his own reflected glory. Six years later yet again, he outd[id] himself with a fearless return to retro.\"<ref name=\"Christgau2\"/> [[Elton John]], a fan of Saadiq's music since his beginnings with Tony! Toni! Ton\u00e9!, said that he was \"blown away\" by ''The Way I See It'', citing it as \"my album of the year \u2013 a soul record of the highest quality.\"<ref name=\"John\"/> He subsequently called Saadiq to congratulate him for the album and ask him to play at his [[Elton John AIDS Foundation Academy Award Party|AIDS Foundation Academy Award Party]] in 2009.<ref name=\"John\">{{cite journal |last=John |first=Elton |authorlink=Elton John |date=April 18, 2012 |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2111975_2111976_2111949,00.html |title=Raphael Saadiq \u2013 2012 TIME 100 The Most Influential People in the World |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |location=New York |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Asua4O6Q?url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2111975_2111976_2111949,00.html |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In an interview for ''Blues & Soul'', Saadiq elaborated on the album's impact on his career: \"before that record \u2013 after I'd been in Tony Toni Tone! and [[Lucy Pearl]] \u2013 most people had thought 'Oh well, he's a producer now. He\u2019s never gonna be an artist, he's not gonna put the time in' ... ''The Way I See It'' showed them that yes, I could put the time in still and be an artist!\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lewis |first=Pete |url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/658/old_skool_new_cool/ |title=Raphael Saadiq: Putting the cool in ol' skool |journal=Blues & Soul |location=London |issue=1041 |date=April 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Asud5zR1?url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/658/old_skool_new_cool/ |archivedate=September 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1 = Sure Hope You Mean It\n| writer1 = [[Raphael Saadiq]]\n| extra1 = Raphael Saadiq\n| length1 = 3:40\n\n| title2 = [[100 Yard Dash]]\n| writer2 = {{hlist|[[Jake and the Phatman|Bobby Ozuna]]|Saadiq}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Raphael Saadiq|Bobby Ozuna{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length2 = 2:18\n\n| title3 = Keep Marchin'\n| writer3 = Saadiq\n| extra3 = Raphael Saadiq\n| length3 = 2:37\n\n| title4 = Big Easy\n| note4 = featuring The Infamous Young Spodie and [[Rebirth Brass Band|The Rebirth Brass Band]]\n| writer4 = Saadiq\n| extra4 = Raphael Saadiq\n| length4 = 3:18\n\n| title5 = Just One Kiss\n| note5 = featuring [[Joss Stone]]\n| writer5 = Saadiq\n| extra5 = Raphael Saadiq\n| length5 = 2:32\n\n| title6 = [[Love That Girl]]\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Ozuna|Saadiq}}\n| extra6 = {{hlist|Raphael Saadiq|Bobby Ozuna{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length6 = 3:04\n\n| title7 = Calling\n| note7 = featuring Rocio Mendoza\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Rocio Mendoza|Saadiq}}\n| extra7 = Raphael Saadiq\n| length7 = 3:44\n\n| title8 = Staying in Love\n| writer8 = Saadiq\n| extra8 = Raphael Saadiq\n| length8 = 