tps://www.webcitation.org/6AplV0DlD?url=http://muzyka.onet.pl/plyty/katalog/raphael-saadiq-the-way-i-see-it,133756,plyta.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|April 6, 2009\n|[[Sony BMG]]\n|-\n|Germany<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computerbild.de/artikel/Musikkritik-Rock-Pop-The-Way-I-See-It-4262694.html |title=CD-Kritik: Raphael Saadiq \u2013 The Way I See It |publisher=Computer Bild. Teleschau |language=German |date=April 17, 2009 |accessdate=May 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AplQsgtj?url=http://www.computerbild.de/artikel/Musikkritik-Rock-Pop-The-Way-I-See-It-4262694.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|April 17, 2009\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Sony Music Entertainment]]\n|-\n|Ireland<ref>{{cite journal|date=February 24, 2009 |url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/5271215.html |title=Raphael Saadiq for Vicar St |journal=[[Hot Press]] |location=Dublin |accessdate=September 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AplHrrto?url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/5271215.html |archivedate=September 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|April 27, 2009\n|-\n|United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hmv.com/hmvweb/displayProductDetails.do?ctx=280;0;-1;-1;-1&sku=911332 |title=Raphael Saadiq: Way I See It (2009): CD |publisher=HMV |accessdate=October 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6BDZpqy5m?url=http://hmv.com/hmvweb/displayProductDetails.do?ctx=280;0;-1;-1;-1&sku=911332 |archivedate=2012-10-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|R&B and Soul Music}}\n* [[Sleeper hit]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite news|last=Powers|first=Ann|authorlink=Ann Powers|date=September 7, 2008|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-caw-soul7-2008sep07,0,5287783.story|title=Ne-Yo, Keri Hilson and the style that lasts: R&B|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.raphaelsaadiq.com/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150103043008/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A4986.htm ''The Way I See It''] at [[Acclaimed Music]] (list of accolades)\n* {{Discogs master|157237|The Way I See It|type=album}}\n* {{MusicBrainz release group|id=35185c28-a4aa-3061-9eb3-1d6741f85609|name=The Way I See It}}\n\n{{Raphael Saadiq}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Way I See It, The}}\n[[Category:2008 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Raphael Saadiq]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records albums]]\n[[Category:Raphael Saadiq albums]]\n", "name_user": "TheAmazingPeanuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Way_I_See_It"}
{"title_page": "Elections in South Korea", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Politics of South Korea}}\n'''Elections in South Korea''' are held on national level to select the [[President of South Korea|President]] and the [[National Assembly of South Korea|National Assembly]]. Local elections are held every four years to elect governors, metropolitan mayors, municipal mayors, and provincial and municipal legislatures.\n\nThe president is directly elected for a single five-year term by [[Plurality voting system|plurality]] vote. The National Assembly has 300 members elected for a four-year term, 253 in single-seat [[constituency|constituencies]] and 47 members by [[proportional representation]]. Each individual party willing to represent its policies in the National Assembly is qualified on the legislative (general) election if: i) the national party-vote reaches over 3% on proportional contest or ii) more than 5 members of the party are elected from each of their [[first-past-the-post]] election constituencies.<ref>[http://www.intergraphy.com/nec_english/overview/overview_represen01.asp Representation System(Elected Person)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422022730/http://www.intergraphy.com/nec_english/overview/overview_represen01.asp |date=April 22, 2008 }}, the NEC, Retrieved on April 10, 2008</ref>\n\nSince the [[2020 South Korean legislative election|2020 legislative elections]], South Korea has two main parties, the liberal [[Democratic Party of Korea]] and the right-wing populist [[United Future Party]]. In addition, there are currently two notable minor (non-aligned) parties: the liberal-conservative centrist [[Party for People's Livelihoods]] & the progressive [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice Party]].\n\n==Election Technology==\n[[File:Korean 5th local election ballot paper - Muju na.jpg|thumb|South Korean ballots from 2010.]]\n[[Polling place]]s are usually located in schools.  During the\nabsentee or [[early voting]] period, voters can vote at any polling place in the country.  On [[election day]], voters may only vote at polling places in their registered constituency.  Korean voters mark [[paper ballot]]s with a [[rubber stamp]] using red ink.  There is one race per ballot paper; if there are multiple office up for election, ballot papers are color coded and voters are issued one ballot per race.<ref name=\"MeisburgerKorea\">Tim Meisburger, [http://asiafoundation.org/2016/04/20/korean-elections-a-model-of-best-practice/ Korean Elections: A Model of Best Practice], April 20, 2016.</ref>\n\nKorea uses a [[Voting machine#Central-count voting system|central count]] model.  After the polls close, ballot boxes are sealed and transported to the constituency's counting center.  Traditionally ballots were hand counted, and [[Optical scan voting system|optical scanners]] have been adopted since [[2002 South Korean local elections|3rd local elections]] held on 13 June 2002. The scanners resemble [[cash sorter machine]]s, sorting the ballots into stacks by how they are voted.  Stacks are then counted using machines resembling [[currency counting machine]]s.<ref name=\"OglimKorea\">Oglim, [http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-931053 The South Korean 2012 Presidential Election was Fraudulent], Feb. 21, 2013. ([https://web.archive.org/web/20130715164454/http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-931053 archived version].)</ref>\n\nKorean elections have been praised as a model of best practice.<ref name=\"MeisburgerKorea\"/>  However, the legality of the introduction of optical scan technology has been challenged and there have been allegations of rigged counting.<ref name=\"OglimKorea\" />\n\n==Schedule==\n\n===Election===\n{|class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Position !! 2017 !! 2018 !! 2019 !! 2020 !! 2021 !! 2022\n|-\n!Type\n| [[2017 South Korean presidential election|Presidential (May)]] || [[2018 South Korean local elections|Local (June)]] || None || [[2020 South Korean legislative 